INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server administrator receives alerts that a Windows Server 2022 system is experiencing intermittent blue screen errors (BSODs) with the stop code MEMORY_MANAGEMENT. The server has four 16 GB DDR4 ECC RAM modules installed across all available DIMM slots. The errors appear most frequently during peak workload hours. Which sequence of troubleshooting steps is MOST appropriate to isolate the faulty component?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Immediately replace all four RAM modules with new ones, then monitor the server for 48 hours to confirm stability."},{"id":"b","text":"Run the Windows Memory Diagnostic tool, then if errors are found, test each DIMM individually by reseating one module at a time in a known-good slot and re-running the diagnostic after each swap."},{"id":"c","text":"Reinstall the operating system to eliminate software corruption as the root cause, then evaluate hardware only if BSODs persist."},{"id":"d","text":"Update the server firmware and BIOS to the latest version, then increase the virtual memory page file size to compensate for the failing RAM."}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Option B is correct because it follows a systematic, evidence-based troubleshooting methodology. Running the Windows Memory Diagnostic (or a tool like MemTest86) first confirms that RAM is the actual source of the MEMORY_MANAGEMENT BSOD, rather than a driver or OS issue. After confirming a memory fault, isolating each DIMM individually in a known-good slot narrows the failure to a specific module, minimizing unnecessary component replacement and downtime. Option A is incorrect because replacing all modules at once is wasteful and does not identify which module is faulty. Option C is incorrect because a MEMORY_MANAGEMENT stop code with ECC RAM strongly points to a hardware fault; reinstalling the OS addresses software-layer problems and wastes time without addressing the likely root cause. Option D is incorrect because expanding the page file does not fix faulty physical RAM and could mask the problem temporarily while leaving a dangerous instability in production.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/drivers/debugger/bug-check-0x1a--memory-management","label":"Microsoft Learn – MEMORY_MANAGEMENT Bug Check (0x0000001A)"},{"url":"https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/diagnosing-memory-problems-on-your-computer-6c58570f-9b0d-8f0e-0e5d-2c960e56e8e8","label":"Microsoft Support – Using Windows Memory Diagnostic Tool"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-prior-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server administrator receives alerts that a Windows Server 2022 system is experiencing intermittent blue screen errors (BSODs) with the stop code MEMORY_MANAGEMENT. The server has four 16 GB DDR4 ECC RAM modules installed across all available DIMM slots. The errors appear most frequently during peak workload hours. Which sequence of troubleshooting steps is MOST appropriate to isolate the faulty component?$patch$);
