INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server's iDRAC (Integrated Dell Remote Access Controller) is accessible via the network, but an administrator cannot log in using the documented credentials. No other administrator has recently changed the password. Which of the following is the BEST course of action?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Perform a factory reset of the iDRAC via the physical system UEFI interface to restore default credentials"},{"id":"b","text":"Reinstall the server's operating system to reset iDRAC authentication"},{"id":"c","text":"Replace the server's system board to reset the embedded management controller"},{"id":"d","text":"Reconfigure the iDRAC IP address from the OS to force a credential refresh"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When iDRAC credentials are unknown or locked and no administrator has changed them, performing a factory reset of the iDRAC through the physical server's UEFI/BIOS setup (Lifecycle Controller or iDRAC Settings utility) restores default factory credentials without affecting the OS or data. Reinstalling the OS does not affect iDRAC credentials, which are stored in the management controller's non-volatile memory. Replacing the system board is a destructive and costly action not warranted here. Reconfiguring the iDRAC IP from the OS does not reset authentication credentials.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.dell.com/support/kbdoc/en-us/000126703/how-to-reset-the-idrac-to-factory-defaults","label":"Dell Technologies – Resetting iDRAC to Factory Default Settings"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server's iDRAC (Integrated Dell Remote Access Controller) is accessible via the network, but an administrator cannot log in using the documented credentials. No other administrator has recently changed the password. Which of the following is the BEST course of action?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server that was recently migrated to a new rack cannot reach its default gateway, although its IP address, subnet mask, and gateway settings appear correct. Other servers in the same rack communicate without issue. Which of the following should the administrator check FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Verify that the server's VLAN tag matches the access or trunk VLAN configured on the switch port"},{"id":"b","text":"Confirm that the server's hostname resolves correctly in DNS"},{"id":"c","text":"Check whether the server's ARP table has the correct MAC for the default gateway"},{"id":"d","text":"Reboot the switch to clear its ARP and MAC address tables"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$After a rack migration, the physical switch port the server is now connected to may be assigned to a different VLAN than the server's network requires. A VLAN mismatch means the server and gateway are on different broadcast domains and Layer 2 frames will never reach the gateway, even though IP settings are correct. DNS resolution is irrelevant when the server cannot reach its default gateway at Layer 3. An ARP table issue is a symptom, not a root cause. Rebooting a switch is disruptive and unnecessary as a first step.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/vlan/b_179_vlan_9300_cg/configuring_vlans.html","label":"Cisco – VLAN Configuration Guide"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server that was recently migrated to a new rack cannot reach its default gateway, although its IP address, subnet mask, and gateway settings appear correct. Other servers in the same rack communicate without issue. Which of the following should the administrator check FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During a scheduled backup window, a tape backup job consistently fails with an error indicating that the backup media is not writable. The tape drive and tapes are new. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The tape cartridge write-protect tab is in the protected position"},{"id":"b","text":"The backup software license has expired, disabling write functionality"},{"id":"c","text":"The tape drive's SCSI ID conflicts with another device on the same bus"},{"id":"d","text":"The backup job is scheduled outside the maintenance window defined in the software"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$A physical write-protect tab on a tape cartridge being in the protected (locked) position is the most common and easily overlooked reason a new tape cartridge is reported as not writable. Backup software such as Veeam, Backup Exec, or similar tools will return a media-not-writable error in this case. A SCSI ID conflict would prevent the tape drive from being detected at all, not just writes. An expired software license would typically block all backup operations, not report a media error. Maintenance window restrictions cause scheduling errors, not media errors.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.quantum.com/en/support/documentation/","label":"Quantum – LTO Tape Cartridge Handling Guide"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During a scheduled backup window, a tape backup job consistently fails with an error indicating that the backup media is not writable. The tape drive and tapes are new. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server running a web application returns HTTP 503 errors intermittently. CPU and memory utilization on the server appear normal. The application logs show no errors. Which of the following should the administrator investigate NEXT?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Analyze network switch port statistics for packet loss and errors"},{"id":"b","text":"Check the load balancer's connection pool and health check configuration"},{"id":"c","text":"Review the web server's maximum file descriptor (open files) limit"},{"id":"d","text":"Inspect the SSL/TLS certificate expiration date"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$HTTP 503 (Service Unavailable) errors that are intermittent, with normal server resource utilization and clean application logs, strongly suggest the problem lies in front of the application — typically a load balancer that is marking the server unhealthy or exhausting its connection pool. The load balancer's health check may be misconfigured, causing it to intermittently remove the backend. Switch-level packet loss would typically manifest as TCP retransmissions, not clean 503s. File descriptor limits would show errors in application or OS logs. An expired SSL certificate causes 503/SSL handshake errors but consistently, not intermittently.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.nginx.com/nginx/admin-guide/load-balancer/http-load-balancer/","label":"NGINX Documentation – HTTP Load Balancing"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server running a web application returns HTTP 503 errors intermittently. CPU and memory utilization on the server appear normal. The application logs show no errors. Which of the following should the administrator investigate NEXT?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server generates repeated alerts for ECC memory errors on DIMM slot 4. The errors are correctable single-bit errors (SBEs). The server has been stable so far. What is the MOST appropriate next step?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Immediately power down the server and replace the DIMM"},{"id":"b","text":"Increase the memory scrubbing interval to reduce ECC event frequency"},{"id":"c","text":"Monitor the DIMM for uncorrectable errors (UEs) and schedule proactive replacement during the next maintenance window"},{"id":"d","text":"Disable ECC memory to prevent further alerts and maintain server performance"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Single-bit ECC errors are correctable and do not immediately threaten data integrity. However, increasing SBE frequency on a specific DIMM is a reliable predictor of impending module failure. The best practice is to proactively schedule the DIMM's replacement during the next maintenance window while monitoring for uncorrectable errors (UEs), which would require immediate action. Immediately powering down a production server for a correctable error is unnecessarily disruptive. Disabling ECC is dangerous as it removes the only protection against memory bit errors. Adjusting scrub intervals does not address the root cause.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.dell.com/support/kbdoc/en-us/000137001/understanding-memory-single-bit-and-multi-bit-errors-in-poweredge-servers","label":"Dell Technologies – Understanding ECC Memory Events"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server generates repeated alerts for ECC memory errors on DIMM slot 4. The errors are correctable single-bit errors (SBEs). The server has been stable so far. What is the MOST appropriate next step?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After a routine firmware update on a server's RAID controller, the operating system fails to detect any drives. The RAID controller is recognized in the UEFI. Which of the following should the administrator do FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Reinstall the operating system on a new drive"},{"id":"b","text":"Replace the RAID controller with a newer model"},{"id":"c","text":"Roll back the RAID controller firmware to the previous version"},{"id":"d","text":"Update the HBA driver within the operating system"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Since the issue appeared immediately after a firmware update and the RAID controller is recognized by UEFI, the most likely cause is a firmware bug or incompatibility introduced by the update. Rolling back the firmware is the least destructive and most targeted first step. Reinstalling the OS would destroy data and is premature. Replacing the controller is a costly step that should only be considered after other remediation has failed. Updating the OS HBA driver could help, but cannot be done if the OS does not boot due to missing drives.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.broadcom.com/support/knowledgebase/1211161498377/how-to-downgrade-megaraid-controller-firmware","label":"Broadcom – MegaRAID Firmware Rollback Guide"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After a routine firmware update on a server's RAID controller, the operating system fails to detect any drives. The RAID controller is recognized in the UEFI. Which of the following should the administrator do FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator notices that a server's network throughput is significantly below expected capacity despite the NIC being rated for 10 Gbps. A cable test confirms the cable is good. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The NIC is operating in half-duplex mode due to a duplex mismatch with the switch"},{"id":"b","text":"The server's firewall is throttling outbound traffic"},{"id":"c","text":"The NIC's MAC address has not been registered in the switch's MAC address table"},{"id":"d","text":"Flow control is enabled on the switch but disabled on the server NIC"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$A duplex mismatch between a NIC and a switch port is a very common cause of severely degraded throughput. If one side is set to full-duplex and the other auto-negotiates to half-duplex, the half-duplex device will detect collisions and back off, causing massive throughput reduction and increased errors. A firewall would not inherently throttle traffic without a configured rate-limit rule. An unregistered MAC address would simply result in flooded frames but not reduced throughput. Flow control mismatches cause occasional pauses but rarely the severe throughput reduction seen with duplex mismatches.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/ethernet/10561-3.html","label":"Cisco – Configuring and Troubleshooting Ethernet Half-Duplex and Full-Duplex Mismatch"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator notices that a server's network throughput is significantly below expected capacity despite the NIC being rated for 10 Gbps. A cable test confirms the cable is good. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server running Windows Server 2022 suddenly reboots and generates a BSOD with the stop code MEMORY_MANAGEMENT (0x0000001A). Which of the following tools should the administrator use FIRST to diagnose potential RAM faults?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Performance Monitor (perfmon)"},{"id":"b","text":"Windows Memory Diagnostic (mdsched.exe)"},{"id":"c","text":"Resource Monitor (resmon)"},{"id":"d","text":"Disk Cleanup (cleanmgr)"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The MEMORY_MANAGEMENT stop code (0x0000001A) indicates a severe memory subsystem error in Windows. Windows Memory Diagnostic (mdsched.exe) is the built-in Microsoft tool that performs extended RAM tests across multiple passes to identify faulty memory modules. Performance Monitor and Resource Monitor are real-time performance tools that cannot test physical RAM integrity. Disk Cleanup is unrelated to memory diagnostics.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/diagnose-memory-problems-on-your-pc-a7d5a021-9b9e-4e03-b8cc-2a2bc8a27e3a","label":"Microsoft Support – Windows Memory Diagnostic"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/drivers/debugger/bug-check-0x1a--memory-management","label":"Microsoft – Bug Check 0x1A: MEMORY_MANAGEMENT"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server running Windows Server 2022 suddenly reboots and generates a BSOD with the stop code MEMORY_MANAGEMENT (0x0000001A). Which of the following tools should the administrator use FIRST to diagnose potential RAM faults?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A virtual machine running on a Type-1 hypervisor host suddenly becomes unresponsive. Other VMs on the same host continue to function normally. The VM's virtual disk is stored on a shared SAN. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The hypervisor host has experienced a kernel panic"},{"id":"b","text":"The VM has exhausted its allocated vCPU resources due to a runaway process"},{"id":"c","text":"The SAN LUN mapped to this VM has gone offline or lost connectivity"},{"id":"d","text":"The virtual NIC driver inside the VM is incompatible with the hypervisor version"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Because other VMs on the same host continue to operate normally, a host-level kernel panic is ruled out. A VM becoming unresponsive while stored on a SAN is a classic indicator that the LUN or storage path has become unavailable — the VM's I/O requests block indefinitely, causing it to hang. A runaway process would typically cause high CPU usage visible in the hypervisor console, not full unresponsiveness. A NIC driver incompatibility would affect network connectivity only, not overall VM responsiveness.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://docs.vmware.com/en/VMware-vSphere/8.0/vsphere-storage/GUID-9D567C12-8E53-4BED-892F-2633E5B78ADA.html","label":"VMware Documentation – Troubleshooting Storage"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A virtual machine running on a Type-1 hypervisor host suddenly becomes unresponsive. Other VMs on the same host continue to function normally. The VM's virtual disk is stored on a shared SAN. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator discovers that a server's CPU temperature consistently reads 95°C under normal load. The server is not in a high-ambient-temperature environment. Which of the following should be checked FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Verify that the correct TDP-rated power supply is installed"},{"id":"b","text":"Check that the CPU heat sink is properly seated and thermal paste is applied correctly"},{"id":"c","text":"Confirm that the CPU model matches the motherboard's supported CPU list"},{"id":"d","text":"Inspect BIOS settings for incorrect CPU voltage multiplier configuration"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$95°C under normal load strongly suggests a thermal interface problem. An improperly seated heat sink or dried/missing/incorrectly applied thermal paste drastically reduces heat transfer from the CPU die to the heat sink. This is the most common and easiest-to-verify cause. PSU TDP ratings do not affect CPU temperature directly. CPU-motherboard compatibility issues would prevent POST, not cause high temperatures. Voltage multiplier misconfiguration is a less common scenario and would be accompanied by system instability or failure to boot.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.intel.com/content/www/us/en/support/articles/000005835/processors.html","label":"Intel – Thermal Interface Material Application"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator discovers that a server's CPU temperature consistently reads 95°C under normal load. The server is not in a high-ambient-temperature environment. Which of the following should be checked FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server's POST process halts and emits a pattern of three short beeps followed by one long beep. The server has no video output. Which component should the technician investigate FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Hard disk drive"},{"id":"b","text":"System RAM (memory modules)"},{"id":"c","text":"CPU heat sink and fan"},{"id":"d","text":"Network interface card"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Beep codes during POST are generated by the system BIOS/UEFI firmware to indicate hardware faults detected before video initializes. While beep code patterns vary by BIOS vendor, combinations involving multiple short beeps frequently indicate RAM failures. No video output combined with beep codes is a classic symptom of a memory error, as the GPU and display cannot be initialized without functional RAM. HDDs, CPUs with fan issues, and NICs have distinct or no beep codes and typically do not prevent video initialization.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.ibm.com/docs/en/power10?topic=codes-post-beep","label":"IBM – POST beep codes"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server's POST process halts and emits a pattern of three short beeps followed by one long beep. The server has no video output. Which component should the technician investigate FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Users report that a server running a business-critical application responds slowly only during business hours. You review performance data and find that disk I/O wait time exceeds 60% during peak periods. The server has a single SATA SSD. Which corrective action would MOST effectively address this bottleneck?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Increase the server's RAM to reduce pagefile utilization"},{"id":"b","text":"Upgrade the SATA SSD to an NVMe SSD or implement a storage array"},{"id":"c","text":"Add a second CPU to increase available processing threads"},{"id":"d","text":"Increase the size of the application's log buffer to reduce write frequency"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$An I/O wait time of 60% clearly indicates the disk subsystem is the bottleneck, not the CPU or RAM. Upgrading from SATA SSD to NVMe provides significantly higher IOPS and lower latency. Adding a storage array distributes I/O. Adding RAM could help only if paging is the primary driver of disk I/O, which is not indicated here. Adding a second CPU does not relieve disk I/O. Increasing log buffer size may slightly reduce writes but will not address the fundamental throughput limitation.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/monitoring_and_managing_system_status_and_performance/setting-the-disk-scheduler_monitoring-and-managing-system-status-and-performance","label":"Red Hat Documentation – Understanding I/O Schedulers"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Users report that a server running a business-critical application responds slowly only during business hours. You review performance data and find that disk I/O wait time exceeds 60% during peak periods. The server has a single SATA SSD. Which corrective action would MOST effectively address this bottleneck?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Windows Server 2022 system log shows repeated Event ID 41 (Kernel-Power) entries. The server restarts without a BSOD or error message. Which of the following is the MOST likely root cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"A corrupted Windows Update file causing kernel panic"},{"id":"b","text":"Unexpected power loss to the server, possibly due to a failing PSU or UPS"},{"id":"c","text":"An incompatible device driver causing a silent system crash"},{"id":"d","text":"The server's automatic restart on BSOD setting is disabled"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Event ID 41 Kernel-Power is logged when the system restarts without a clean shutdown sequence, most commonly caused by sudden power loss. A failing PSU or UPS that cuts power without warning produces this event. A BSOD caused by a driver would typically generate Event ID 1001 (BugCheck) alongside the restart. Corrupted Windows Update files generally cause setup errors, not spontaneous reboots. The automatic restart setting affects whether a BSOD triggers a reboot but still generates a BugCheck event.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/topic/event-id-41-the-system-has-rebooted-without-cleanly-shutting-down-first-99650383-b988-c963-4f9e-f0f6d1ea94a9","label":"Microsoft Support – Event ID 41: The system has rebooted without cleanly shutting down first"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Windows Server 2022 system log shows repeated Event ID 41 (Kernel-Power) entries. The server restarts without a BSOD or error message. Which of the following is the MOST likely root cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux server boots to a read-only filesystem after an unplanned power loss. Attempts to remount the filesystem as read-write fail with errors referencing journal corruption. Which tool should the administrator use to resolve this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"fdisk"},{"id":"b","text":"mkfs"},{"id":"c","text":"fsck"},{"id":"d","text":"parted"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$fsck (filesystem consistency check) is the correct tool to repair filesystem corruption including journal errors on Linux ext2/ext3/ext4 filesystems. It must be run on an unmounted or read-only-mounted filesystem. fdisk and parted are partition management tools and do not repair filesystem corruption. mkfs formats a filesystem, destroying all data, which is not an appropriate first step.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://linux.die.net/man/8/fsck","label":"Linux man page – fsck"},{"url":"https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/managing_file_systems/checking-and-repairing-a-file-system_managing-file-systems","label":"Red Hat Documentation – Checking and Repairing a File System"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux server boots to a read-only filesystem after an unplanned power loss. Attempts to remount the filesystem as read-write fail with errors referencing journal corruption. Which tool should the administrator use to resolve this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After replacing a failed drive in a RAID 5 array, the array begins rebuilding but the server performance degrades severely and the rebuild never completes. Which of the following should you investigate FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Verify that the replacement drive capacity meets or exceeds the original drive capacity"},{"id":"b","text":"Check the RAID controller battery backup unit (BBU) charge level"},{"id":"c","text":"Inspect remaining drives in the array for reallocated sector counts using S.M.A.R.T. data"},{"id":"d","text":"Confirm that the server's power supply wattage is sufficient for the additional drive"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$During a RAID 5 rebuild, every remaining drive must be read. If another drive in the array has reallocated sectors or is beginning to fail (visible via S.M.A.R.T. data), read errors will stall or halt the rebuild. This is the most common reason a RAID 5 rebuild does not complete. While BBU health affects write-back caching performance, it does not prevent rebuild completion. Drive capacity and PSU wattage are generally validated before a rebuild begins.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.seagate.com/support/kb/understanding-s-m-a-r-t-smart-data-178705en/","label":"Seagate – Understanding S.M.A.R.T."}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After replacing a failed drive in a RAID 5 array, the array begins rebuilding but the server performance degrades severely and the rebuild never completes. Which of the following should you investigate FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server intermittently loses network connectivity every few hours. The NIC driver and firmware are up to date. You notice the issue correlates with high CPU utilization spikes. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Faulty network switch port causing CRC errors"},{"id":"b","text":"Interrupt Request (IRQ) conflict between the NIC and another PCI device"},{"id":"c","text":"The NIC's TCP Offload Engine (TOE) is disabled in the OS"},{"id":"d","text":"An incorrect subnet mask assigned to the server interface"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$IRQ conflicts between PCI devices can cause intermittent NIC failures that worsen under high CPU load, because the CPU cannot service conflicting interrupt requests fast enough. A faulty switch port would typically show persistent errors, not CPU-correlated ones. Disabling TOE increases CPU usage but does not cause loss of connectivity. An incorrect subnet mask would cause consistent, not intermittent, connectivity issues.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/drivers/kernel/introduction-to-interrupt-affinity","label":"Microsoft Docs – Interrupt Affinity"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server intermittently loses network connectivity every few hours. The NIC driver and firmware are up to date. You notice the issue correlates with high CPU utilization spikes. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A systems administrator needs to ensure that only authorized USB storage devices can be used on production servers to prevent data exfiltration. Which of the following controls BEST enforces this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Disable USB ports physically using port blockers on all servers"},{"id":"b","text":"Implement a Device Control policy via endpoint security software that whitelists approved USB device identifiers"},{"id":"c","text":"Post a security policy reminder in the server room prohibiting unauthorized USB use"},{"id":"d","text":"Enable BitLocker To Go to encrypt all USB drives used in the environment"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$A Device Control policy enforced by endpoint security software allows administrators to whitelist specific USB devices by hardware ID, vendor ID, or serial number, technically preventing unauthorized devices from mounting while permitting approved ones. Physical port blockers (Option A) prevent all USB use — both authorized and unauthorized — making legitimate administrative use impossible and failing the requirement for authorized device use. A posted policy reminder (Option C) is an administrative control that relies on human compliance and cannot technically enforce the restriction. BitLocker To Go (Option D) encrypts data on the drive but does not prevent unauthorized devices from connecting and potentially exfiltrating data.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-53/rev-5/final","label":"NIST SP 800-53 Rev. 5 – MP-7 Media Use"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/defender-endpoint/control-usb-devices-using-intune","label":"Microsoft – Control USB devices and other removable media using Microsoft Defender for Endpoint"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A systems administrator needs to ensure that only authorized USB storage devices can be used on production servers to prevent data exfiltration. Which of the following controls BEST enforces this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator is reviewing server logs and notices multiple failed login attempts followed by a successful login from an unfamiliar IP address at 3:00 AM. The account used belongs to a senior developer who is currently on vacation. Which type of attack has MOST likely occurred?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"ARP poisoning"},{"id":"b","text":"Brute-force or credential-stuffing attack leading to unauthorized access"},{"id":"c","text":"SQL injection attack"},{"id":"d","text":"Man-in-the-middle (MITM) attack"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The pattern of multiple failed logins followed by a successful login from an unfamiliar external IP — especially targeting a known account when its owner is unavailable to detect anomalies — is the hallmark of a brute-force or credential-stuffing attack that eventually succeeded. ARP poisoning (Option A) operates at Layer 2 within the local network and would not appear as repeated failed logins from an external IP. SQL injection (Option C) targets application databases, not server login interfaces. MITM (Option D) intercepts traffic in transit and would not typically produce multiple failed login attempts in the server logs.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-61/rev-2/final","label":"NIST SP 800-61 Rev. 2 – Computer Security Incident Handling Guide"},{"url":"https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Credential_Stuffing_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html","label":"OWASP – Credential Stuffing Prevention Cheat Sheet"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator is reviewing server logs and notices multiple failed login attempts followed by a successful login from an unfamiliar IP address at 3:00 AM. The account used belongs to a senior developer who is currently on vacation. Which type of attack has MOST likely occurred?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company performs monthly disaster recovery tests and consistently finds that the restored servers cannot communicate on the network after failover. After each test, engineers manually reconfigure IP addressing. Which DR planning element was MOST likely neglected?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The disaster recovery runbook did not include network configuration steps or IP address schemas for the DR site"},{"id":"b","text":"The backup retention period was set too short"},{"id":"c","text":"The recovery point objective was not clearly defined"},{"id":"d","text":"Server hardware at the DR site is incompatible with production backups"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$A disaster recovery runbook must include detailed, step-by-step network configuration instructions — including IP addressing, subnets, default gateways, and DNS settings for the DR environment. The recurring need for manual reconfiguration after every test indicates these steps were missing from the documented plan. Backup retention (Option B) affects how far back you can restore, not network connectivity. RPO definition (Option C) governs acceptable data loss, not post-failover networking. Hardware incompatibility (Option D) would prevent restoration entirely, not cause network communication failures on successfully restored servers.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-34/rev-1/final","label":"NIST SP 800-34 Rev. 1 – IT Contingency Plan Development"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives – Disaster Recovery Concepts"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company performs monthly disaster recovery tests and consistently finds that the restored servers cannot communicate on the network after failover. After each test, engineers manually reconfigure IP addressing. Which DR planning element was MOST likely neglected?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization is classifying its data assets as part of a new security policy. Which of the following data types would MOST likely be classified at the HIGHEST sensitivity level and require encryption both at rest and in transit?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Publicly available marketing brochures stored on a web server"},{"id":"b","text":"Aggregated and anonymized website traffic statistics"},{"id":"c","text":"Personally Identifiable Information (PII) combined with financial account numbers"},{"id":"d","text":"Internal IT asset inventory spreadsheets"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Personally Identifiable Information (PII) combined with financial account numbers falls under the most sensitive data classification because its exposure carries significant legal liability, regulatory penalties (e.g., GDPR, PCI-DSS), and harm to individuals. Encryption at rest and in transit is a baseline requirement for such data. Public marketing materials (Option A) require no special protection. Anonymized statistics (Option B) are generally low-sensitivity. Internal asset inventories (Option D) are internal/confidential but do not carry the same regulatory weight or individual harm potential.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-53/rev-5/final","label":"NIST SP 800-53 Rev. 5 – RA-2 Security Categorization"},{"url":"https://www.pcisecuritystandards.org/document_library/","label":"PCI DSS v4.0 – Requirement 3: Protect Stored Account Data"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization is classifying its data assets as part of a new security policy. Which of the following data types would MOST likely be classified at the HIGHEST sensitivity level and require encryption both at rest and in transit?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server administrator is designing a fault-tolerant storage solution for a server that hosts a high-transaction database. The solution must survive the simultaneous failure of two hard drives without data loss. Which RAID level BEST meets this requirement with the fewest total drives needed?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"RAID 5"},{"id":"b","text":"RAID 6"},{"id":"c","text":"RAID 10"},{"id":"d","text":"RAID 1"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$RAID 6 uses dual distributed parity, allowing the array to sustain two simultaneous drive failures without data loss, with a minimum of four drives. RAID 5 (Option A) uses single parity and can only survive one drive failure. RAID 10 (Option C) can survive two drive failures only in certain configurations (mirrored pairs), and requires a minimum of four drives but uses 50% of capacity for mirroring — it is not the most drive-efficient solution for this specific dual-failure tolerance requirement. RAID 1 (Option D) mirrors two drives and can only survive one failure per mirror pair.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives – RAID Levels"},{"url":"https://www.snia.org/education/storage_networking_primer/stor_mgmt/ch07","label":"SNIA – RAID Levels Overview"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server administrator is designing a fault-tolerant storage solution for a server that hosts a high-transaction database. The solution must survive the simultaneous failure of two hard drives without data loss. Which RAID level BEST meets this requirement with the fewest total drives needed?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During a security audit, it is discovered that several service accounts on a Windows server have the 'Password Never Expires' flag set and use the same shared password. Which security principle is MOST directly violated by this configuration?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Defense in depth"},{"id":"b","text":"Least privilege"},{"id":"c","text":"Separation of duties"},{"id":"d","text":"Principle of non-repudiation"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The principle of least privilege requires that accounts be granted only the minimum necessary access and that credentials be tightly controlled. Shared passwords and non-expiring passwords mean multiple parties share elevated access with no individual accountability, directly violating least privilege and individual accountability norms. Defense in depth (Option A) is a layered security strategy — not specific to credential management. Separation of duties (Option C) refers to dividing critical tasks among multiple people, which is a separate concern. Non-repudiation (Option D) is about ensuring actions cannot be denied, though shared accounts do undermine it — the most direct violation here is least privilege.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-53/rev-5/final","label":"NIST SP 800-53 Rev. 5 – AC-6 Least Privilege"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/identity/ad-ds/manage/service-accounts/service-accounts-overview","label":"Microsoft – Service Account Security Best Practices"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During a security audit, it is discovered that several service accounts on a Windows server have the 'Password Never Expires' flag set and use the same shared password. Which security principle is MOST directly violated by this configuration?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization wants to harden a newly provisioned server. Which of the following actions represents the MOST effective first step in server hardening?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable the host-based firewall and allow all outbound traffic by default"},{"id":"b","text":"Apply the latest OS patches and firmware updates before placing the server in production"},{"id":"c","text":"Rename the local Administrator account and set a complex password"},{"id":"d","text":"Install antivirus software and run a full system scan"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Applying current OS patches and firmware updates before production deployment closes known vulnerabilities that attackers could exploit, making it the highest-priority first step in any hardening process. Renaming the Administrator account (Option C) and enabling a firewall (Option A) are valid hardening steps but address a narrower attack surface. Installing antivirus (Option D) is important but is less impactful than eliminating known OS/firmware vulnerabilities immediately. Security frameworks such as CIS Benchmarks and NIST consistently list patching as the foundational step.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.cisecurity.org/cis-benchmarks/","label":"CIS Benchmarks – Server Hardening Guidelines"},{"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-123/final","label":"NIST SP 800-123 – Guide to General Server Security"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization wants to harden a newly provisioned server. Which of the following actions represents the MOST effective first step in server hardening?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company's data center experiences a complete power failure lasting four hours. The servers are protected by a UPS, but the UPS batteries are only rated for 15 minutes of runtime. Which technology would have BEST ensured continuous server operation during this extended outage?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"A redundant power supply unit (PSU) in each server"},{"id":"b","text":"A standby generator connected to an automatic transfer switch (ATS)"},{"id":"c","text":"A larger capacity UPS with extended battery modules"},{"id":"d","text":"Power distribution units (PDUs) with remote monitoring capabilities"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$A standby generator connected to an Automatic Transfer Switch (ATS) automatically starts and transfers the electrical load when utility power fails, providing extended runtime well beyond what any battery system can supply. This is the standard solution for outages lasting hours. A redundant PSU (Option A) protects against a failed power supply but not a facility-wide power outage. A larger UPS (Option C) still has finite battery life and would eventually fail during a four-hour outage. Remote PDUs (Option D) provide monitoring and outlet control but do not generate power.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives – Power and Environmental Controls"},{"url":"https://www.apc.com/us/en/faqs/FA158852/","label":"APC by Schneider Electric – Generator and UPS Integration Guide"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company's data center experiences a complete power failure lasting four hours. The servers are protected by a UPS, but the UPS batteries are only rated for 15 minutes of runtime. Which technology would have BEST ensured continuous server operation during this extended outage?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator needs to ensure that all administrative access to production servers is logged, sessions are recorded, and access is brokered through a single control point. Which solution BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Implement a RADIUS authentication server"},{"id":"b","text":"Deploy a Privileged Access Workstation (PAW) for all admins"},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy a Privileged Access Management (PAM) solution with session recording"},{"id":"d","text":"Enforce multi-factor authentication on all server logins"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$A Privileged Access Management (PAM) solution provides a centralized broker for privileged sessions, enforces least-privilege, and records sessions for audit purposes — directly satisfying all three stated requirements. RADIUS (Option A) handles authentication but does not broker or record sessions. A PAW (Option B) is a hardened workstation for admin use but does not provide centralized session brokering or recording. MFA (Option D) strengthens authentication but does not record sessions or centralize access control.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-53/rev-5/final","label":"NIST SP 800-53 Rev. 5 – AC-17 Remote Access & AU-14 Session Audit"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-identity-manager/pam/privileged-identity-management-for-active-directory-domain-services","label":"Microsoft – Privileged Access Management Overview"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator needs to ensure that all administrative access to production servers is logged, sessions are recorded, and access is brokered through a single control point. Which solution BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which of the following BEST describes the purpose of a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) in a disaster recovery plan?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The maximum tolerable amount of data loss measured in time"},{"id":"b","text":"The maximum acceptable length of time to restore a system to full operation after a disaster"},{"id":"c","text":"The frequency at which backups must be performed"},{"id":"d","text":"The geographic distance required between primary and disaster recovery sites"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Recovery Time Objective (RTO) defines the maximum acceptable duration of time within which a business process must be restored after a disruption to avoid unacceptable consequences. Option A describes Recovery Point Objective (RPO), which measures tolerable data loss. Option C describes backup frequency policy, not RTO. Option D refers to site separation guidelines, which are separate from RTO definitions.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-34/rev-1/final","label":"NIST SP 800-34 Rev. 1 – Contingency Planning Guide for Federal Information Systems"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ Certification Exam Objectives SK0-005"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which of the following BEST describes the purpose of a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) in a disaster recovery plan?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server administrator is implementing a backup strategy for a critical database server. The organization requires that data can be restored to any point within the last 30 days, while minimizing storage consumption. Which backup strategy BEST meets these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Daily full backups retained for 30 days"},{"id":"b","text":"Weekly full backups combined with daily differential backups"},{"id":"c","text":"Weekly full backups combined with daily incremental backups and transaction log backups"},{"id":"d","text":"Monthly full backups combined with weekly incremental backups"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Weekly full backups combined with daily incremental backups and transaction log backups provide granular point-in-time recovery within the 30-day window while using significantly less storage than daily full backups. Transaction log backups allow recovery to any specific point in time. Option A uses the most storage. Option B (differential) grows larger each day between fulls and does not provide point-in-time recovery. Option D does not support 30-day granular restore since the monthly full is too infrequent.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Study Guide – Backup Strategies"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/sql/relational-databases/backup-restore/back-up-and-restore-of-sql-server-databases","label":"Microsoft – SQL Server Backup and Restore Overview"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server administrator is implementing a backup strategy for a critical database server. The organization requires that data can be restored to any point within the last 30 days, while minimizing storage consumption. Which backup strategy BEST meets these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$While planning the installation of a high-density blade server enclosure in an existing data center rack, a technician must calculate the total power draw to ensure the PDU circuit is not overloaded. The enclosure is rated at 8.5 kW maximum. The facility uses 208 V single-phase circuits with a 30 A breaker, and best practice dictates loading a breaker to no more than 80% of its rated capacity. Which of the following BEST describes whether this enclosure can safely run on a single 30 A / 208 V circuit?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Yes, because 208 V × 30 A = 6,240 W, which is under the 8.5 kW enclosure maximum"},{"id":"b","text":"No, because the 80% derated capacity of the circuit is 4,992 W, which is less than the 8.5 kW enclosure maximum"},{"id":"c","text":"Yes, because data center equipment is exempt from the 80% breaker loading rule"},{"id":"d","text":"No, because blade enclosures always require three-phase power and cannot use single-phase circuits"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The maximum safe (derated) capacity of the circuit is calculated as: 208 V × 30 A × 0.80 = 4,992 W (approximately 5 kW). The blade enclosure's maximum draw of 8.5 kW far exceeds this safe limit, so the enclosure cannot safely run on a single 30 A / 208 V single-phase circuit. Option A is incorrect because it ignores the mandatory 80% NEC derating rule — the full 6,240 W capacity must never be used continuously, and even the full 6,240 W is still less than 8.5 kW. Option C is incorrect because data center equipment is not exempt from NEC 80% continuous load derating; this rule applies universally to continuous loads. Option D is incorrect because while three-phase power is common for high-density enclosures, it is not an absolute requirement — the real issue here is total power capacity.$patch$, $patch$Server Hardware Installation and Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.nfpa.org/codes-and-standards/nfpa-70-standard-development/70","label":"NFPA 70 – National Electrical Code (NEC) Article 210.20, Continuous Loads"},{"url":"https://www.ashrae.org/technical-resources/bookstore/datacom-series","label":"ASHRAE – Data Center Power and Cooling Guidelines"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$While planning the installation of a high-density blade server enclosure in an existing data center rack, a technician must calculate the total power draw to ensure the PDU circuit is not overloaded. The enclosure is rated at 8.5 kW maximum. The facility uses 208 V single-phase circuits with a 30 A breaker, and best practice dictates loading a breaker to no more than 80% of its rated capacity. Which of the following BEST describes whether this enclosure can safely run on a single 30 A / 208 V circuit?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A technician is tasked with installing four 2.5-inch hot-swap NVMe drives into a rack server that currently has eight populated SATA drive bays. The server's backplane supports both SATA and NVMe. After installing the NVMe drives, two of them are not detected by the system. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The NVMe drives exceed the maximum storage capacity supported by the server chassis"},{"id":"b","text":"The PCIe lanes available to the NVMe controller are insufficient to support all four drives simultaneously"},{"id":"c","text":"NVMe drives cannot share a backplane with SATA drives and require a dedicated backplane"},{"id":"d","text":"The RAID controller needs to be replaced with an HBA before NVMe drives can be used"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$NVMe drives communicate over PCIe lanes rather than using a SATA/SAS protocol. Each NVMe drive requires dedicated PCIe lane allocation from the CPU or PCIe switch on the backplane. If the server's PCIe lane budget is exhausted, additional NVMe drives will not be detected. This is a common constraint when mixing large numbers of NVMe devices. Option A is incorrect because drive capacity does not affect detection. Option C is incorrect because many modern tri-mode backplanes support both SATA and NVMe on the same backplane. Option D is incorrect because NVMe drives typically bypass the RAID controller entirely and connect directly via PCIe; replacing the RAID controller with an HBA does not resolve a PCIe lane limitation.$patch$, $patch$Server Hardware Installation and Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://nvmexpress.org/education/nvme-technology-overview/","label":"NVM Express – NVMe Architecture Overview"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A technician is tasked with installing four 2.5-inch hot-swap NVMe drives into a rack server that currently has eight populated SATA drive bays. The server's backplane supports both SATA and NVMe. After installing the NVMe drives, two of them are not detected by the system. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server technician is installing a new dual-processor server and notices that after seating both CPUs, the system only recognizes one processor during POST. The second CPU socket shows no activity. Which of the following should the technician check FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Verify that the BIOS/UEFI firmware supports multi-processor configurations and update if necessary"},{"id":"b","text":"Replace the second CPU with a known-good spare from a different processor family"},{"id":"c","text":"Reseat the second CPU and inspect the socket for bent or damaged pins"},{"id":"d","text":"Reinstall the operating system to include multi-processor HAL drivers"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When a second CPU is not recognized during POST, the most common physical causes are an improperly seated processor or physical damage (bent/missing pins) to the CPU or socket. Reseating and inspecting the CPU socket is the correct first step following a 'simplest physical cause first' troubleshooting methodology. Updating firmware (option A) may eventually be required but is premature before verifying physical installation. Swapping with a different processor family (option B) would be incorrect because CPUs in a multi-socket board must match in model and stepping. Reinstalling the OS (option D) is irrelevant because the issue occurs at POST, before the OS loads.$patch$, $patch$Server Hardware Installation and Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Candidate Guide"},{"url":"https://www.intel.com/content/www/us/en/support/articles/000005805/boards-and-kits.html","label":"Intel – Dual-Processor Server Board Installation Guide"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P1$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server technician is installing a new dual-processor server and notices that after seating both CPUs, the system only recognizes one processor during POST. The second CPU socket shows no activity. Which of the following should the technician check FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server technician is installing a new dual-processor server and notices that after seating both CPUs, the system only detects one processor during POST. The second CPU socket appears physically undamaged. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause of this issue?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The second CPU is not supported by the current firmware version"},{"id":"b","text":"The second CPU requires a separate power connector that has not been attached"},{"id":"c","text":"The system board only supports asymmetric multiprocessing"},{"id":"d","text":"The second CPU thermal paste application was too thick"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When a second CPU is installed and not detected during POST, one of the most common root causes is a firmware (UEFI/BIOS) version that does not yet support the stepping or model of the newly installed processor. The firmware microcode must be updated to recognize the new CPU. A missing power connector would typically prevent the entire system from booting or trigger a power fault, not selectively hide one CPU. Asymmetric multiprocessing is a software/OS configuration concept, not a hardware detection issue. Thermal paste thickness affects cooling performance, not CPU detection.$patch$, $patch$Server Hardware Installation and Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.intel.com/content/www/us/en/support/articles/000006631/processors.html","label":"Intel – Processor Microcode and BIOS Updates"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server technician is installing a new dual-processor server and notices that after seating both CPUs, the system only detects one processor during POST. The second CPU socket appears physically undamaged. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause of this issue?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A technician is adding a fourth 3.5-inch SAS hard drive to a server chassis. After installation the drive is not enumerated by the OS. The HBA shows no errors and the backplane is powered. Which of the following should the technician check FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Verify that the SAS expander firmware is up to date"},{"id":"b","text":"Confirm that the SAS data cable is fully seated in both the backplane and HBA connectors"},{"id":"c","text":"Replace the HBA with one that supports a higher port count"},{"id":"d","text":"Reformat the drive using the server's built-in diagnostic utility"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Following a systematic troubleshooting approach, the simplest and most common physical cause of a drive not being enumerated—when power is confirmed and the HBA reports no errors—is a SAS data cable that is not fully seated. This should be verified before pursuing firmware updates, hardware replacements, or drive-level operations. Replacing the HBA is premature since no port-count error has been reported. Reformatting the drive addresses a logical issue, not a detection issue.$patch$, $patch$Server Hardware Installation and Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.broadcom.com/doc/12353333","label":"Broadcom – SAS HBA Installation Guide"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A technician is adding a fourth 3.5-inch SAS hard drive to a server chassis. After installation the drive is not enumerated by the OS. The HBA shows no errors and the backplane is powered. Which of the following should the technician check FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During a planned memory upgrade, a technician installs four 32 GB DDR4 RDIMMs into a server that previously had four 16 GB RDIMMs. The server boots but only reports 96 GB of installed RAM instead of the expected 128 GB. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"One of the new DIMMs is faulty and is being ignored by the memory controller"},{"id":"b","text":"The server's UEFI does not support memory modules above 16 GB per slot"},{"id":"c","text":"The old 16 GB DIMMs were not fully removed from all slots"},{"id":"d","text":"DDR4 RDIMMs require ECC to be enabled before the full capacity is reported"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$96 GB is exactly what you would get if three 32 GB DIMMs and one 16 GB DIMM are installed (3 × 32 + 1 × 16 = 112 GB — actually, the most straightforward arithmetic that yields 96 GB is three 32 GB modules: 3 × 32 = 96 GB), meaning one slot still contains the original 16 GB DIMM that was not replaced. The technician should verify that all four original modules were removed before the new ones were seated. A single faulty DIMM being silently ignored is possible but less common than a simple removal oversight. UEFI DIMM capacity limits would prevent booting or show an error, not partial detection. ECC enablement does not affect reported capacity.$patch$, $patch$Server Hardware Installation and Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.kingston.com/us/memory/server-memory","label":"Kingston Technology – Server Memory Installation Guide"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During a planned memory upgrade, a technician installs four 32 GB DDR4 RDIMMs into a server that previously had four 16 GB RDIMMs. The server boots but only reports 96 GB of installed RAM instead of the expected 128 GB. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A rack technician is installing a 2U server into a rack that uses threaded (cage-nut) rails. After mounting, the technician notices the server's front bezel does not sit flush with the rack's front frame and is angled downward. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The rear rail brackets are mounted one rack unit higher than the front brackets"},{"id":"b","text":"The cable management arm is exerting downward pressure on the server"},{"id":"c","text":"The server chassis is too heavy for the selected rail kit"},{"id":"d","text":"The rack is not properly leveled on the data center floor"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When the rear rail brackets are mounted at a different rack unit position than the front brackets, the server chassis is forced into an angle rather than sitting horizontally. This is the classic cause of a bezel that angles up or down. A cable management arm applies horizontal or slight upward tension, not a downward angle at the front. Exceeding the rail weight rating would cause the rails to sag symmetrically, not angle the bezel. An unleveled rack affects the entire rack column, not a single server's bezel alignment.$patch$, $patch$Server Hardware Installation and Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.dell.com/support/kbdoc/en-us/000126587/poweredge-rack-installation-best-practices","label":"Dell Technologies – Rack Installation Best Practices"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A rack technician is installing a 2U server into a rack that uses threaded (cage-nut) rails. After mounting, the technician notices the server's front bezel does not sit flush with the rack's front frame and is angled downward. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server administrator needs to add a GPU accelerator card to an existing 1U server for an AI inference workload. The card requires a 300 W TDP and a x16 PCIe 4.0 slot. The server has an available x16 slot but the power supply is already operating at 78% load. Which of the following should the administrator address BEFORE installing the card?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Flash the PCIe slot to PCIe 5.0 to provide additional bandwidth for the GPU"},{"id":"b","text":"Upgrade or add a power supply unit to ensure sufficient headroom for the additional 300 W load"},{"id":"c","text":"Install a riser card to convert the x16 slot to a x8 slot to reduce power draw"},{"id":"d","text":"Enable PCIe power management in the UEFI to cap the GPU's power consumption automatically"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Best practice is to keep PSU utilization below 80% under peak load to maintain efficiency and reliability. Adding a 300 W GPU to a PSU already at 78% load would push utilization well above 100% capacity, risking system instability or PSU failure. The administrator must upgrade to a higher-wattage PSU or add a second PSU in a redundant configuration before installation. Flashing PCIe version affects bandwidth, not power delivery. Converting to x8 reduces bandwidth but does not reduce power consumption. PCIe power management can limit performance but is not a substitute for adequate physical power delivery.$patch$, $patch$Server Hardware Installation and Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.nvidia.com/datacenter/tesla/pdf/NVIDIA_MGX_Power_and_Cooling_Guide.pdf","label":"NVIDIA – GPU Power and Cooling Considerations"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server administrator needs to add a GPU accelerator card to an existing 1U server for an AI inference workload. The card requires a 300 W TDP and a x16 PCIe 4.0 slot. The server has an available x16 slot but the power supply is already operating at 78% load. Which of the following should the administrator address BEFORE installing the card?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A technician is replacing a hot-swap power supply in a redundant (1+1) configuration server while it remains online. After removing the failed unit, the technician inserts the replacement PSU and hears a click but the new PSU's LED remains amber. Which of the following is the MOST appropriate next step?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Power down the server, reseat the PSU, and power the server back on"},{"id":"b","text":"Check that the replacement PSU's wattage and form factor match the installed PSU"},{"id":"c","text":"Immediately remove the amber PSU to prevent damage to the server"},{"id":"d","text":"Update the server's iDRAC/iLO firmware to clear the amber status"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$An amber LED on a newly inserted hot-swap PSU typically indicates a mismatch or fault condition. The most common cause when a replacement unit is sourced is a wattage or form factor mismatch—the server's power management subsystem detects that the replacement PSU does not match the specification of the installed unit and flags it. Verifying compatibility is the most appropriate next step before any other action. Powering down defeats the purpose of hot-swap and risks a service outage on a functioning system. Removing the PSU immediately is unnecessary; an amber LED is a warning, not a critical failure requiring instant removal. Firmware updates do not resolve a hardware mismatch.$patch$, $patch$Server Hardware Installation and Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://support.hpe.com/hpesc/public/docDisplay?docId=sd00001293en_us","label":"HPE – Hot-Plug Power Supply Installation Guide"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A technician is replacing a hot-swap power supply in a redundant (1+1) configuration server while it remains online. After removing the failed unit, the technician inserts the replacement PSU and hears a click but the new PSU's LED remains amber. Which of the following is the MOST appropriate next step?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data center engineer is deploying a new server that will be connected to two separate PDUs for power redundancy. The server has two power supply units. Which of the following cabling practices BEST ensures true power redundancy?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Connect both PSUs to the same PDU using separate circuit breakers"},{"id":"b","text":"Connect PSU 1 to PDU A and PSU 2 to PDU B, with each PDU fed from a separate upstream UPS or circuit"},{"id":"c","text":"Connect both PSUs to PDU A and use a KVM switch to manage failover"},{"id":"d","text":"Connect PSU 1 to PDU A and leave PSU 2 unplugged as a cold spare"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$True power redundancy requires that each PSU be fed from a completely independent power path—separate PDUs, each with its own upstream UPS or utility circuit. This ensures that if one entire power path (PDU, UPS, or circuit) fails, the server continues operating on the surviving path. Connecting both PSUs to the same PDU eliminates redundancy because a PDU failure takes down both PSUs simultaneously. A KVM switch is a keyboard/video/mouse device and has no role in power redundancy. An unplugged cold-spare PSU provides no live redundancy.$patch$, $patch$Server Hardware Installation and Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.apc.com/us/en/faqs/FA156065/","label":"APC by Schneider Electric – Data Center Power Redundancy Best Practices"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data center engineer is deploying a new server that will be connected to two separate PDUs for power redundancy. The server has two power supply units. Which of the following cabling practices BEST ensures true power redundancy?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$When installing a server into a high-density rack, a technician must select the correct torque specification when securing the server's mounting screws to the rack rails. Which of the following BEST explains why over-torquing the screws is a concern?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Over-torquing can strip the threads on the rack rail's cage nuts or the server chassis, compromising the mechanical integrity of the mount"},{"id":"b","text":"Over-torquing generates excessive heat that can damage nearby power cables"},{"id":"c","text":"Over-torquing activates the server chassis intrusion sensor and locks the UEFI"},{"id":"d","text":"Over-torquing increases the risk of electrostatic discharge between the server and the rack"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Applying excessive torque to mounting screws strips the threads on either the cage nuts or the server chassis mounting points. Stripped threads cannot securely hold the server, meaning the chassis may shift or fall, creating a safety hazard and potentially damaging hardware. Heat generation from screw torquing is negligible and localized, posing no practical risk to power cables. Chassis intrusion sensors are triggered by panel removal, not screw torque. ESD is related to static charge, not mechanical torque.$patch$, $patch$Server Hardware Installation and Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.dell.com/support/kbdoc/en-us/000142785/how-to-properly-install-and-secure-servers-in-a-dell-rack","label":"Dell Technologies – Rack Mounting Safety and Torque Specifications"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$When installing a server into a high-density rack, a technician must select the correct torque specification when securing the server's mounting screws to the rack rails. Which of the following BEST explains why over-torquing the screws is a concern?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A technician is installing a new NVMe U.2 SSD into a server that currently uses SATA SSDs. The technician seats the U.2 drive into an available drive bay. The drive bay backplane is connected to the server's PCIe HBA. After rebooting, the NVMe drive is not detected. Which of the following is the MOST likely reason?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"NVMe U.2 drives are incompatible with 2.5-inch drive bays designed for SATA SSDs"},{"id":"b","text":"The backplane does not support NVMe and only routes SATA signals to the drive bays"},{"id":"c","text":"The HBA must be replaced with a RAID controller to support NVMe drives"},{"id":"d","text":"NVMe drives require a dedicated 12 V power cable not provided by the U.2 connector"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$U.2 (SFF-8639) uses the same physical connector and form factor as SATA SSDs, so a U.2 NVMe drive will fit physically into a SATA bay. However, NVMe communicates over PCIe lanes, not SATA signal lines. If the backplane only routes SATA signals—not PCIe lanes—to the drive bays, the NVMe drive will not be detected regardless of the PCIe HBA present. The drive bay backplane must explicitly support NVMe (routing PCIe signals) for U.2 NVMe drives to function. Physical form factor is the same; it is the signal routing that differs. RAID controllers are not required to detect a drive. The U.2 connector provides all necessary power, including 12 V, natively.$patch$, $patch$Server Hardware Installation and Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://nvmexpress.org/education/nvme-u-2-interface/","label":"NVM Express – U.2 Interface Overview"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A technician is installing a new NVMe U.2 SSD into a server that currently uses SATA SSDs. The technician seats the U.2 drive into an available drive bay. The drive bay backplane is connected to the server's PCIe HBA. After rebooting, the NVMe drive is not detected. Which of the following is the MOST likely reason?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server administrator is implementing a backup strategy for a critical database server. The organization requires that recovery point objectives (RPO) be no greater than 24 hours, and recovery time objectives (RTO) be no greater than 4 hours. Full backups are performed every Sunday at midnight and take approximately 3 hours to restore. Which backup strategy should the administrator implement to meet BOTH the RPO and RTO requirements while minimizing backup storage consumption?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Perform full backups every Sunday and differential backups every weekday night"},{"id":"b","text":"Perform full backups every Sunday and incremental backups every weekday night"},{"id":"c","text":"Perform full backups every Sunday and mirror backups every weekday night"},{"id":"d","text":"Perform full backups every night of the week"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Differential backups capture all changes since the last full backup. To restore, you need only the last full backup and the most recent differential — meaning at most two restore operations, keeping RTO feasible within 4 hours. Differential backups also consume less storage than nightly full backups (option D). Incremental backups (option B) consume the least storage but require restoring the full backup PLUS every incremental in sequence, which can push the RTO beyond 4 hours as the week progresses. Mirror backups (option C) are a real-time copy strategy and do not inherently meet the described RPO/RTO framework without additional tooling.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives — Backup and Recovery Concepts"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/training/books/server-sk0-005-study-guide","label":"CompTIA Official Study Guide: Backup Types Overview"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server administrator is implementing a backup strategy for a critical database server. The organization requires that recovery point objectives (RPO) be no greater than 24 hours, and recovery time objectives (RTO) be no greater than 4 hours. Full backups are performed every Sunday at midnight and take approximately 3 hours to restore. Which backup strategy should the administrator implement to meet BOTH the RPO and RTO requirements while minimizing backup storage consumption?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company stores sensitive customer data on a file server. The security team mandates that all data on the server's hard drives must be unreadable if the drives are physically removed or stolen. The server runs Windows Server and uses a hardware TPM 2.0 chip. Which technology BEST satisfies this requirement with the least administrative overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable BitLocker Drive Encryption using the TPM 2.0 chip to automatically manage keys"},{"id":"b","text":"Implement an NTFS permission-based access control policy restricting all user accounts"},{"id":"c","text":"Configure a software RAID-1 mirror so data is redundant across two drives"},{"id":"d","text":"Enable the Encrypted File System (EFS) using the default local administrator account"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$BitLocker Drive Encryption with TPM 2.0 provides full-volume encryption that renders the drive unreadable without the correct encryption keys, which are sealed to the TPM — meaning physical removal of the drive gives an attacker only ciphertext. This satisfies the requirement with minimal overhead because the TPM handles key storage automatically. NTFS permissions (option B) control access at the OS level but provide no protection if the drive is removed and accessed outside the OS. RAID-1 (option C) provides redundancy, not encryption, and does not protect against physical theft. EFS (option D) encrypts individual files/folders but is tied to user certificates; using only the local admin account is not a scalable or robust solution and does not protect the entire volume.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/operating-system-security/data-protection/bitlocker/bitlocker-overview","label":"Microsoft Learn — BitLocker Overview"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives — Data Security"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company stores sensitive customer data on a file server. The security team mandates that all data on the server's hard drives must be unreadable if the drives are physically removed or stolen. The server runs Windows Server and uses a hardware TPM 2.0 chip. Which technology BEST satisfies this requirement with the least administrative overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After a ransomware attack encrypted production data on a server, the incident response team attempts to restore from backup. They discover that the ransomware had been silently present on the network for 45 days before triggering, and the organization retains only 30 days of backup history. Which disaster recovery concept did the organization FAIL to adequately plan for?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Recovery Time Objective (RTO)"},{"id":"b","text":"Recovery Point Objective (RPO)"},{"id":"c","text":"Backup retention policy aligned with threat dwell time"},{"id":"d","text":"Geographic redundancy of backup media"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The core failure here is that the backup retention window (30 days) was shorter than the attacker's dwell time (45 days), meaning no clean backup existed to restore from. This is a backup retention policy failure — specifically the policy did not account for the possibility that malware could remain dormant longer than the retention period. RTO (option A) relates to how quickly systems can be restored, which is not the issue described. RPO (option B) defines how much data loss is acceptable in terms of time, but the scenario's problem is not data loss frequency — it is that no uninfected restore point exists at all. Geographic redundancy (option D) addresses offsite storage of backups and is unrelated to the retention duration problem illustrated here.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-209/final","label":"NIST SP 800-209 — Security Guidelines for Storage Infrastructure"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives — Disaster Recovery Planning"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After a ransomware attack encrypted production data on a server, the incident response team attempts to restore from backup. They discover that the ransomware had been silently present on the network for 45 days before triggering, and the organization retains only 30 days of backup history. Which disaster recovery concept did the organization FAIL to adequately plan for?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server administrator needs to harden a newly deployed Linux server that will host internal web applications. After reviewing the CompTIA Server+ security hardening checklist, which action MOST effectively reduces the server's attack surface at the network level?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Rename the root account to a non-obvious username"},{"id":"b","text":"Disable all non-essential services and close unused ports using a host-based firewall"},{"id":"c","text":"Install antivirus software and schedule daily full-system scans"},{"id":"d","text":"Enable verbose logging on all system services to monitor for anomalies"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Disabling non-essential services and closing unused ports via a host-based firewall (such as iptables or firewalld) directly reduces the server's network attack surface by eliminating potential entry points that attackers could exploit. This is a foundational hardening principle. Renaming the root account (option A) provides minimal security benefit on Linux systems because attackers can still target UID 0 directly, and most modern hardening guides recommend disabling direct root login via SSH instead. Installing antivirus (option C) is a useful detective and protective control but does not directly reduce the network attack surface. Enabling verbose logging (option D) is important for monitoring and incident response but is a detective control that does not proactively close attack vectors.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.cisecurity.org/cis-benchmarks","label":"CIS Benchmarks — Linux Server Hardening Guidelines"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives — Server Hardening"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server administrator needs to harden a newly deployed Linux server that will host internal web applications. After reviewing the CompTIA Server+ security hardening checklist, which action MOST effectively reduces the server's attack surface at the network level?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$What type of documentation helps technicians when troubleshooting user Internet connectivity issues?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"A","text":"Baseline documentation"},{"id":"B","text":"Network documentation"},{"id":"C","text":"Service manuals"},{"id":"D","text":"Dataflow diagrams"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["B"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Correct Answer: Network documentation is correct. Network documentation will identify network links, subnet addresses, server IP addresses and names, default gateways, and so on.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ exam objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-prior-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$What type of documentation helps technicians when troubleshooting user Internet connectivity issues?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server randomly reboots several times per day with no consistent pattern. Event logs show kernel panic entries referencing memory address errors. Which action should the administrator perform FIRST to isolate the root cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Replace the power supply unit immediately"},{"id":"b","text":"Run a memory diagnostic tool such as Memtest86+ on each DIMM slot individually"},{"id":"c","text":"Reinstall the operating system from scratch"},{"id":"d","text":"Update the NIC firmware to the latest version"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Kernel panics referencing memory address errors strongly indicate faulty RAM. Running Memtest86+ on individual DIMM slots isolates which specific module or slot is defective before replacing any hardware. Replacing the PSU or reinstalling the OS would not address a memory fault, and updating NIC firmware is entirely unrelated to memory address errors.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Study Guide – Memory Troubleshooting"},{"url":"https://www.memtest86.com/technical.htm","label":"Memtest86 Official Documentation"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server randomly reboots several times per day with no consistent pattern. Event logs show kernel panic entries referencing memory address errors. Which action should the administrator perform FIRST to isolate the root cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Users report they cannot reach an internal web application hosted on a Windows Server 2022 machine. The server itself can ping its own IP address and the default gateway. Remote servers on the same subnet CANNOT ping the affected server. Which is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The server's NIC is configured with the wrong duplex setting"},{"id":"b","text":"Windows Defender Firewall is blocking inbound ICMP and HTTP traffic"},{"id":"c","text":"The web application service has crashed and needs to be restarted"},{"id":"d","text":"DNS is not resolving the server's hostname correctly"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Because the server can ping its own IP and the gateway but remote hosts on the same subnet cannot ping it, the issue is most likely an inbound firewall rule blocking ICMP echo requests and HTTP traffic. A duplex mismatch would cause degraded throughput, not total connectivity loss. A crashed web service would still allow ICMP. DNS is irrelevant when testing by IP address.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/operating-system-security/network-security/windows-firewall/windows-firewall-with-advanced-security","label":"Microsoft Learn – Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Users report they cannot reach an internal web application hosted on a Windows Server 2022 machine. The server itself can ping its own IP address and the default gateway. Remote servers on the same subnet CANNOT ping the affected server. Which is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux server's RAID 5 array shows one disk member in a degraded state after a sudden power outage. The server has redundant power supplies. What is the administrator's FIRST step before replacing the failed drive?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Immediately hot-swap the degraded disk with a new one"},{"id":"b","text":"Back up all critical data from the array before performing any hardware changes"},{"id":"c","text":"Upgrade the RAID controller firmware"},{"id":"d","text":"Convert the RAID 5 array to RAID 6 while it is degraded"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$A degraded RAID 5 array has no remaining fault tolerance; if a second disk fails during rebuild, all data is lost. Backing up data first is the safest first step. Immediately hot-swapping without a backup is risky. Upgrading firmware or converting RAID levels during a degraded state could further destabilize the array.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/managing_storage_devices/managing-raid_managing-storage-devices","label":"Red Hat – Managing RAID"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux server's RAID 5 array shows one disk member in a degraded state after a sudden power outage. The server has redundant power supplies. What is the administrator's FIRST step before replacing the failed drive?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator notices that a server's CPU utilization consistently spikes to 100% every day at 2:00 AM. The spikes last approximately 15 minutes. System performance is unaffected during business hours. Which is the MOST likely cause of this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The server is overheating and throttling the CPU"},{"id":"b","text":"A scheduled task or cron job is running a resource-intensive process at that time"},{"id":"c","text":"The server has been infected with ransomware"},{"id":"d","text":"The BIOS power management settings are incorrect"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Predictable, time-based CPU spikes that recur at the same time each day and have a defined duration are classic symptoms of a scheduled task or cron job, such as antivirus scans, backups, or index rebuilds. Overheating would produce random throttling with alerts. Ransomware is typically constant or random. BIOS power management would not cause a 15-minute-window spike at a specific time.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/taskschd/task-scheduler-start-page","label":"Microsoft Learn – Task Scheduler Overview"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/cron.8.html","label":"Linux man page – cron"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator notices that a server's CPU utilization consistently spikes to 100% every day at 2:00 AM. The spikes last approximately 15 minutes. System performance is unaffected during business hours. Which is the MOST likely cause of this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A technician replaces a failed network switch port by moving a server's cable to a new port. After the move, the server cannot communicate on the network. The link light on the new port is active. Which is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The new port is assigned to a different VLAN than the server requires"},{"id":"b","text":"The server's NIC driver needs to be updated"},{"id":"c","text":"The server's IP address lease has expired"},{"id":"d","text":"The new switch port has PoE enabled, which is disrupting the server NIC"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When a cable is moved to a new switch port and connectivity fails while the link light is on, VLAN misconfiguration is the most common cause. The new port may be in a different VLAN, preventing the server from reaching its default gateway or other hosts. NIC driver issues would exist regardless of port. An expired DHCP lease would be resolved by the client requesting a new one. PoE does not disrupt server-grade NICs in a way that prevents communication.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Study Guide – Network Troubleshooting"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/vlan/b_179_vlan_9300_cg.html","label":"Cisco – VLAN Configuration Guide"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A technician replaces a failed network switch port by moving a server's cable to a new port. After the move, the server cannot communicate on the network. The link light on the new port is active. Which is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server running Windows Server 2022 reports Event ID 2019 in the System event log. An administrator observes that performance is sluggish and virtual memory usage is extremely high. What does Event ID 2019 specifically indicate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The server has run out of nonpaged pool memory"},{"id":"b","text":"A disk volume is approaching capacity"},{"id":"c","text":"A critical Windows service has stopped unexpectedly"},{"id":"d","text":"The system time is out of sync with the domain controller"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Event ID 2019 (Source: Srv) indicates that the server has run out of nonpaged pool memory, meaning the kernel cannot allocate memory that must remain in physical RAM and cannot be paged to disk. This causes severe performance degradation. Disk capacity warnings use different event IDs. Service failures generate Event ID 7034 or similar. Time sync issues generate Event IDs under the W32Time source.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/troubleshoot/windows-server/performance/non-paged-pool-memory-depleted","label":"Microsoft Learn – Event ID 2019"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server running Windows Server 2022 reports Event ID 2019 in the System event log. An administrator observes that performance is sluggish and virtual memory usage is extremely high. What does Event ID 2019 specifically indicate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After a firmware update on a server, the iDRAC/BMC management interface is no longer reachable over the network, but the server itself continues to operate normally. Which troubleshooting step should be performed FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Perform a cold reboot of the main server operating system"},{"id":"b","text":"Reset the BMC/iDRAC to factory defaults using the physical reset button or BIOS option"},{"id":"c","text":"Replace the server motherboard"},{"id":"d","text":"Roll back the main OS kernel to the previous version"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$A firmware update can reset or corrupt BMC/iDRAC network configuration settings. The most targeted first step is to reset the BMC/iDRAC using the dedicated hardware reset button or the in-BIOS option, which restores network settings without disrupting the production OS. A full OS reboot would not fix the out-of-band management interface. Replacing the motherboard is destructive and premature. Rolling back the OS kernel does not affect BMC firmware.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.dell.com/support/manuals/en-us/idrac9-lifecycle-controller-v5.x-series/idrac9_5.xx_ug/introduction-to-idrac9","label":"Dell – iDRAC User Guide"},{"url":"https://support.hpe.com/hpesc/public/docDisplay?docId=a00018631en_us","label":"HPE – iLO Troubleshooting Guide"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After a firmware update on a server, the iDRAC/BMC management interface is no longer reachable over the network, but the server itself continues to operate normally. Which troubleshooting step should be performed FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server's POST process halts and emits a series of beep codes: one long beep followed by three short beeps. The server has an AMI BIOS. Which component should the technician inspect FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The hard disk drives"},{"id":"b","text":"The video/graphics card or video memory"},{"id":"c","text":"The network interface card"},{"id":"d","text":"The CPU fan"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$For AMI BIOS, one long beep followed by three short beeps indicates a video memory failure or a faulty graphics adapter. The technician should reseat or replace the video card first. Hard disk errors would not cause a POST beep code in this pattern. NICs and CPU fans do not generate this specific AMI BIOS beep code sequence.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.ami.com/bios/","label":"AMI BIOS Beep Code Reference"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server's POST process halts and emits a series of beep codes: one long beep followed by three short beeps. The server has an AMI BIOS. Which component should the technician inspect FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator is troubleshooting a server that cannot boot after a BIOS configuration change. The server now shows a 'No bootable device found' error. The drives and RAID array are confirmed to be healthy. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The BIOS boot order was changed and no longer points to the correct boot device"},{"id":"b","text":"The operating system has become corrupted"},{"id":"c","text":"The RAID controller has failed"},{"id":"d","text":"Secure Boot has detected an unsigned bootloader"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When a 'No bootable device found' error appears immediately after a BIOS configuration change and the drives are confirmed healthy, the BIOS boot order is the first thing to verify. A BIOS change could have altered the boot sequence to prioritize a device that has no bootable OS. OS corruption and RAID failure are ruled out since the array is healthy. Secure Boot issues would typically show a more specific error message about signature validation.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/manufacture/desktop/boot-to-uefi-mode-or-legacy-bios-mode","label":"Microsoft Learn – Configure BIOS/UEFI Boot Order"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator is troubleshooting a server that cannot boot after a BIOS configuration change. The server now shows a 'No bootable device found' error. The drives and RAID array are confirmed to be healthy. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A physical server hosts four virtual machines. Three VMs are responsive, but one VM becomes unresponsive and cannot be reached via the network. The hypervisor console shows the VM is running. Which troubleshooting action should the administrator take FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Migrate all VMs to another host immediately"},{"id":"b","text":"Access the VM's console directly through the hypervisor management interface and check for OS-level errors"},{"id":"c","text":"Reboot the entire physical host server"},{"id":"d","text":"Increase the vCPU count allocated to the unresponsive VM"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Since the hypervisor shows the VM as running but it is unreachable over the network, the issue is isolated to that VM. Accessing the VM console through the hypervisor (e.g., VMware vSphere Console, Hyper-V VM Connect) allows the administrator to see OS-level errors without disrupting other VMs or the host. Migrating all VMs is unnecessary and disruptive. Rebooting the entire host would impact all three responsive VMs. Increasing vCPU resources does not address a network connectivity or OS hang issue.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://docs.vmware.com/en/VMware-vSphere/8.0/vsphere-vcenter-esxi-management/GUID-4E1A2F57-7C22-4E1A-A7A9-9D4AF954C9E4.html","label":"VMware – Accessing a VM Console"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/virtualization/hyper-v/learn-more/hyper-v-virtual-machine-connect","label":"Microsoft Learn – Hyper-V Virtual Machine Connection"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A physical server hosts four virtual machines. Three VMs are responsive, but one VM becomes unresponsive and cannot be reached via the network. The hypervisor console shows the VM is running. Which troubleshooting action should the administrator take FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server administrator receives an alert that a server's storage volume is at 98% capacity. The server hosts a file share used by 200 users. Which is the BEST immediate action to restore normal operations while a long-term solution is implemented?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Shut down the server to prevent data corruption"},{"id":"b","text":"Identify and remove or archive large unnecessary files to free up space immediately"},{"id":"c","text":"Add a new physical disk and convert to RAID 5 immediately"},{"id":"d","text":"Format the volume and restore from backup"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The best immediate action is to free up disk space quickly without disrupting users by identifying and removing temporary files, log files, or archiving old data. Shutting down would cause an outage. Converting to RAID 5 mid-crisis is time-consuming and complex. Formatting and restoring would cause a significant outage and risks data loss if the backup is not current.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/storage/disk-management/overview-of-disk-management","label":"Microsoft Learn – Manage Disk Space on Windows Server"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server administrator receives an alert that a server's storage volume is at 98% capacity. The server hosts a file share used by 200 users. Which is the BEST immediate action to restore normal operations while a long-term solution is implemented?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server is generating repeated 'Temperature threshold exceeded' alerts from the hardware monitoring system. The ambient room temperature is within normal range. Which of the following should be checked FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Check whether server cooling fans are operational and air vents are not blocked by dust or cable clutter"},{"id":"b","text":"Increase the server's CPU clock speed to finish workloads faster"},{"id":"c","text":"Replace the processor immediately"},{"id":"d","text":"Update the operating system to the latest patch level"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When ambient temperature is normal but the server overheats, the most common causes are failed cooling fans, blocked air vents, or improper airflow inside the chassis. Checking fans and vents is the correct first step. Increasing CPU speed would generate more heat. Replacing the CPU is premature without diagnosis. OS patches do not resolve thermal hardware issues.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives – Environmental Issues"},{"url":"https://www.dell.com/support/kbdoc/en-us/000134682/dell-poweredge-server-thermal-management","label":"Dell PowerEdge – Thermal Management Best Practices"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server is generating repeated 'Temperature threshold exceeded' alerts from the hardware monitoring system. The ambient room temperature is within normal range. Which of the following should be checked FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$While troubleshooting intermittent network packet loss on a server, a technician runs the command 'ethtool eth0' on a Linux server and notices the link speed is negotiated at 100 Mb/s full-duplex instead of the expected 1 Gb/s. Which is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The NIC has a misconfigured or incompatible auto-negotiation setting compared to the switch port"},{"id":"b","text":"The server's CPU is throttling the network throughput"},{"id":"c","text":"The firewall is limiting bandwidth to 100 Mb/s"},{"id":"d","text":"The DNS server is responding slowly, causing the speed cap"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When a NIC negotiates at a lower speed than expected (100 Mb/s instead of 1 Gb/s), the most common cause is an auto-negotiation mismatch between the NIC and the switch port, or a forced speed/duplex setting on one side but not the other. CPU throttling does not limit NIC link speed. Firewalls control traffic flow but do not change the physical link speed. DNS has no effect on physical link negotiation.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/ethtool.8.html","label":"Linux man page – ethtool"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/configuring_and_managing_networking/configuring-network-interface-speed-and-duplex-settings_configuring-and-managing-networking","label":"Red Hat – Configuring Network Interface Speed and Duplex Settings"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$While troubleshooting intermittent network packet loss on a server, a technician runs the command 'ethtool eth0' on a Linux server and notices the link speed is negotiated at 100 Mb/s full-duplex instead of the expected 1 Gb/s. Which is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator receives a 'SMART failure predicted on hard disk' warning during POST on a server with a non-RAID direct-attached storage drive. What is the MOST appropriate FIRST response?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Ignore the warning and continue normal operations since SMART predictions are often inaccurate"},{"id":"b","text":"Immediately back up all data from the affected drive and plan for drive replacement"},{"id":"c","text":"Defragment the drive to resolve the SMART error"},{"id":"d","text":"Disable SMART monitoring in BIOS to prevent future alerts"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$A SMART (Self-Monitoring, Analysis, and Reporting Technology) failure prediction is a strong indicator of impending disk failure. The correct first response is to immediately back up all data and schedule drive replacement. Ignoring the warning risks data loss. Defragmentation has no effect on SMART health indicators. Disabling SMART monitoring eliminates early warning visibility and is never recommended.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.seagate.com/support/kb/using-a-smart-diagnostic-tool-174783en/","label":"Seagate – Understanding SMART"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator receives a 'SMART failure predicted on hard disk' warning during POST on a server with a non-RAID direct-attached storage drive. What is the MOST appropriate FIRST response?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Windows Server 2022 system boots but fails to complete startup, displaying a 'STOP 0x0000007B INACCESSIBLE_BOOT_DEVICE' blue screen. The server was recently migrated from physical hardware to a virtual machine. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The server's system clock drifted too far from the domain controller"},{"id":"b","text":"The storage controller driver required by the virtual environment is not loaded in the OS"},{"id":"c","text":"The server's administrator password was reset during migration"},{"id":"d","text":"Windows activation failed because the hardware profile changed"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Stop code 0x0000007B (INACCESSIBLE_BOOT_DEVICE) typically occurs after a P2V (physical-to-virtual) migration because the original physical server used a specific storage controller driver (e.g., a hardware RAID HBA), while the virtual machine uses a different virtual storage controller (e.g., VMware PVSCSI or Hyper-V VSC). The OS cannot find the boot device because the required driver for the new controller is not loaded. Clock drift, password resets, and Windows activation issues would not produce this specific stop code.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/troubleshoot/windows-client/performance/stop-error-inaccessible-boot-device-after-migration","label":"Microsoft Learn – INACCESSIBLE_BOOT_DEVICE Stop Error"},{"url":"https://docs.vmware.com/en/VMware-vCenter-Converter-Standalone/6.2/com.vmware.convsa.guide/GUID-BCDF4D4D-4E41-4F00-A578-CA3E7AF6C96A.html","label":"VMware – P2V Migration Troubleshooting"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Windows Server 2022 system boots but fails to complete startup, displaying a 'STOP 0x0000007B INACCESSIBLE_BOOT_DEVICE' blue screen. The server was recently migrated from physical hardware to a virtual machine. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server administrator notices that Gigabit Ethernet throughput between two servers on the same switch rarely exceeds 400 Mb/s during large file transfers, even though both NICs and ports are configured for 1 Gb/s full-duplex. CPU utilization on both servers is below 20%. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The NIC interrupt moderation or receive buffer settings are not optimized for throughput"},{"id":"b","text":"The DHCP server is throttling network traffic"},{"id":"c","text":"Both servers need additional physical memory"},{"id":"d","text":"The DNS TTL is set too low, causing excessive lookups"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When link speed is confirmed at 1 Gb/s and CPU utilization is low but throughput is far below line rate, the bottleneck is often NIC-level settings such as interrupt moderation (coalescing), receive/transmit buffer sizes, or offload settings. Tuning these parameters can significantly improve throughput. DHCP servers do not throttle data traffic. Memory affects application performance but not raw NIC throughput at 20% CPU usage. DNS TTL settings have no effect on data transfer speeds.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/configuring_and_managing_networking/optimizing-network-performance-by-using-ethtool_configuring-and-managing-networking","label":"Red Hat – Optimizing Network Performance with ethtool"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/networking/technologies/network-subsystem/net-sub-performance-tuning-nics","label":"Microsoft Learn – Network Adapter Performance Tuning"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server administrator notices that Gigabit Ethernet throughput between two servers on the same switch rarely exceeds 400 Mb/s during large file transfers, even though both NICs and ports are configured for 1 Gb/s full-duplex. CPU utilization on both servers is below 20%. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server's application log shows repeated 'Access Denied' errors when a service account attempts to write to a specific directory. The service account's group membership has not changed. The administrator recently applied a new Group Policy Object (GPO) to the server's OU. Which tool should be used FIRST to determine whether the GPO is changing the directory's NTFS permissions?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Disk Management"},{"id":"b","text":"Resultant Set of Policy (RSoP) or gpresult /r"},{"id":"c","text":"Device Manager"},{"id":"d","text":"Windows Memory Diagnostics"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$RSoP (Resultant Set of Policy) and the 'gpresult /r' command show the effective Group Policy settings applied to a computer or user, allowing the administrator to see if the new GPO is overriding NTFS permissions or applying restrictive security settings to the directory. Disk Management handles partitions and volumes, not permissions. Device Manager handles hardware drivers. Windows Memory Diagnostics tests RAM and is unrelated to file system permissions.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/administration/windows-commands/gpresult","label":"Microsoft Learn – gpresult"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/client-management/mdm/diagnose-mdm-failures-in-windows-10","label":"Microsoft Learn – Resultant Set of Policy"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server's application log shows repeated 'Access Denied' errors when a service account attempts to write to a specific directory. The service account's group membership has not changed. The administrator recently applied a new Group Policy Object (GPO) to the server's OU. Which tool should be used FIRST to determine whether the GPO is changing the directory's NTFS permissions?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In the interest of securing internal network traffic, your boss asks you to ensure that all LAN traffic is encrypted. What should you configure?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"A","text":"Cipher"},{"id":"B","text":"IPSec"},{"id":"C","text":"TLS"},{"id":"D","text":"SSL"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["A"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Correct Answer: IPSec is correct. IP Security (IPSec) can be used to secure any type of network traffic without configuring each piece of software that generates network traffic.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ exam objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-prior-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P2$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In the interest of securing internal network traffic, your boss asks you to ensure that all LAN traffic is encrypted. What should you configure?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which term describes the topmost entity in a PKI?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"A","text":"Public key"},{"id":"B","text":"Certificate authority"},{"id":"C","text":"Private key"},{"id":"D","text":"User PKI certificate"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["A"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Correct Answer: Certificate authority is correct. A certificate authority (CA) is at the top of the Public Key Infrastructure (PKI) hierarchy.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ exam objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-prior-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
