INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which tool is used to troubleshoot suspected server power supplies?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"A","text":"Rescue disk"},{"id":"B","text":"OTDR"},{"id":"C","text":"Multimeter"},{"id":"D","text":"TDR"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["A"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Correct Answer: Multimeter is correct. A multimeter is used to test power supplies.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ exam objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-prior-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which tool is used to troubleshoot suspected server power supplies?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server technician is installing a new dual-socket server with two 12-core processors. After powering on the system, the BIOS only recognizes one CPU. The second CPU socket appears to be unpopulated according to the system inventory. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause of this issue?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The second CPU is not supported by the current BIOS version and requires a firmware update."},{"id":"b","text":"The second CPU was not fully seated in its socket and the retention lever was not locked down properly."},{"id":"c","text":"The system requires matched ECC RAM in both memory channels before a second CPU is recognized."},{"id":"d","text":"The second CPU has a different stepping revision and must be replaced with a matching unit."}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When a BIOS reports a CPU socket as unpopulated immediately after installation, the most common and likely cause is improper seating. CPUs in server-class systems use LGA or LGA-style sockets with a load plate and retention lever (or similar mechanism) that must be fully locked to establish electrical contact across all pins. If the lever is not fully engaged, the CPU will not be detected. A BIOS mismatch (option A) would typically still detect the CPU but flag a compatibility warning. Mismatched RAM (option C) does not prevent CPU detection — the CPU is enumerated before memory training. A different stepping revision (option D) may generate a warning but modern server BIOSes will generally still detect and report both CPUs.$patch$, $patch$Server Hardware Installation and Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.intel.com/content/www/us/en/support/articles/000058909/processors.html","label":"Intel – Server Processor Installation Guidance"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server technician is installing a new dual-socket server with two 12-core processors. After powering on the system, the BIOS only recognizes one CPU. The second CPU socket appears to be unpopulated according to the system inventory. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause of this issue?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data center technician is tasked with installing a new 2U rack server into a fully populated 42U cabinet. The server ships with a static rail kit. Before mounting the server, which of the following steps is MOST important to perform first to ensure a safe and successful installation?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Verify that the cabinet has sufficient power distribution unit (PDU) capacity to support the new server's rated wattage."},{"id":"b","text":"Confirm that two empty contiguous rack units are available at the correct position and that the cabinet's weight load rating will not be exceeded."},{"id":"c","text":"Connect the server to the network switch first to pre-stage the OS image before physically mounting it."},{"id":"d","text":"Flash the server's BMC firmware to the latest version before installation to avoid post-mount access issues."}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Before mounting any new server in a rack, the technician must confirm there are sufficient contiguous rack units available for the server's form factor (2U in this case) and that the total weight of all equipment does not exceed the rack's rated load capacity. Overloading a cabinet is a serious physical safety hazard and can cause structural failure. While PDU capacity (option A) is also important, it is a power planning concern that does not affect the physical safety of the mount itself and is typically evaluated during site planning before equipment arrives. Pre-staging a network OS image (option C) is a logical step but is irrelevant to safe physical installation. BMC firmware updates (option D) are maintenance tasks that are independent of physically mounting the server and are not a prerequisite.$patch$, $patch$Server Hardware Installation and Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.apc.com/us/en/faqs/FA156064/","label":"APC – Data Center Physical Infrastructure: Rack Safety and Weight Planning"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data center technician is tasked with installing a new 2U rack server into a fully populated 42U cabinet. The server ships with a static rail kit. Before mounting the server, which of the following steps is MOST important to perform first to ensure a safe and successful installation?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A technician is upgrading the RAM in a production server from 128 GB to 256 GB by adding eight additional 16 GB DDR4 RDIMMs. After the upgrade and reboot, the server posts successfully but the OS reports only 192 GB of usable memory. Which of the following is the MOST likely explanation?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The new DIMMs are operating in single-channel mode because they were installed in the wrong slots, violating the memory population rules."},{"id":"b","text":"The server's BIOS has a maximum addressable memory limit of 192 GB and requires a firmware update to support more."},{"id":"c","text":"Some of the newly installed DIMMs are not fully seated or are faulty, causing them to be excluded from the memory map."},{"id":"d","text":"The OS is a 32-bit installation and cannot address more than 192 GB of physical RAM."}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When a system posts without error but reports less memory than physically installed, one of the most common causes is that one or more DIMMs are not making reliable contact — either not fully seated in their slots or defective — and are therefore not enumerated in the system memory map. In this scenario, 64 GB is missing (256 GB expected, 192 GB reported), which corresponds to exactly four 16 GB DIMMs being undetected. Option A (wrong slot population) would typically cause a BIOS warning or training failure, not silent exclusion, and would not account for exactly 64 GB missing. Option B is plausible but unlikely on modern server platforms which typically support well above 256 GB; this would also usually be flagged in BIOS release notes. Option D is incorrect because 32-bit operating systems are limited to approximately 4 GB of addressable space, not 192 GB — a server running a 32-bit OS would never report 192 GB.$patch$, $patch$Server Hardware Installation and Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.crucial.com/support/server-memory-installation","label":"Crucial – How to Install Server Memory (DIMM)"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/memory/memory-limits-for-windows-releases","label":"Microsoft – Windows Server Memory Limits"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A technician is upgrading the RAM in a production server from 128 GB to 256 GB by adding eight additional 16 GB DDR4 RDIMMs. After the upgrade and reboot, the server posts successfully but the OS reports only 192 GB of usable memory. Which of the following is the MOST likely explanation?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server administrator needs to ensure that a Linux server automatically mounts a remote NFS share at boot time and that the mount persists across reboots. Which file should the administrator modify to accomplish this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"/etc/hosts"},{"id":"b","text":"/etc/fstab"},{"id":"c","text":"/etc/mtab"},{"id":"d","text":"/etc/exports"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$/etc/fstab (filesystem table) is the correct file to modify in order to configure persistent, automatic mounts on a Linux system, including remote NFS shares. Entries in /etc/fstab are processed at boot time, ensuring the share is mounted automatically on every restart. /etc/hosts is used for static hostname-to-IP address resolution and has no role in mounting filesystems. /etc/mtab is a dynamic file maintained by the kernel that records currently mounted filesystems; it is not edited manually and does not persist mounts across reboots. /etc/exports is used on the NFS *server* side to define which directories are shared with remote clients — it is not used on the client side to mount shares.$patch$, $patch$Server Administration$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/managing_file_systems/assembly_mounting-file-systems_managing-file-systems#proc_persistently-mounting-file-systems_assembly_mounting-file-systems","label":"Red Hat Documentation – Managing the /etc/fstab File"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server administrator needs to ensure that a Linux server automatically mounts a remote NFS share at boot time and that the mount persists across reboots. Which file should the administrator modify to accomplish this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server administrator needs to ensure that data on decommissioned hard drives cannot be recovered by unauthorized parties. Which method provides the MOST thorough sanitization for magnetic HDDs containing sensitive government data?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Quick format the drives using the operating system's built-in tool"},{"id":"b","text":"Perform a single-pass overwrite with zeros using a software tool"},{"id":"c","text":"Degauss the drives followed by physical destruction"},{"id":"d","text":"Delete all partitions and reinstall the operating system"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Degaussing destroys data by exposing magnetic media to a powerful magnetic field, rendering it unreadable. Following degaussing with physical destruction (shredding or crushing) ensures no data can be recovered even with advanced forensic techniques. A quick format or partition deletion only removes file system pointers, leaving raw data intact. A single-pass zero-overwrite may be sufficient for most cases but is generally considered less thorough than degaussing plus destruction for highly sensitive government-classified data, per NIST SP 800-88 guidelines.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/SpecialPublications/NIST.SP.800-88r1.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-88 Rev. 1 – Guidelines for Media Sanitization"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server administrator needs to ensure that data on decommissioned hard drives cannot be recovered by unauthorized parties. Which method provides the MOST thorough sanitization for magnetic HDDs containing sensitive government data?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which backup type copies only the files that have changed since the last full backup and clears the archive bit after each run?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Differential backup"},{"id":"b","text":"Incremental backup"},{"id":"c","text":"Full backup"},{"id":"d","text":"Snapshot backup"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$An incremental backup copies only files that have changed since the last backup of any type (full or incremental) and resets (clears) the archive bit after completing. This makes each incremental backup smaller and faster than a full or differential backup. A differential backup also copies changed files since the last full backup but does NOT clear the archive bit, causing each differential to grow larger over time. A full backup copies all data and clears the archive bit. A snapshot captures the state of a volume at a point in time using pointers, not archive bits.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ Study Guide SK0-005 – Backup Types"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/storage/storage","label":"Microsoft – Backup Types Overview"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which backup type copies only the files that have changed since the last full backup and clears the archive bit after each run?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator wants to protect a server room from unauthorized physical access by requiring both a keycard swipe AND a PIN entry at the same door. Which access control concept does this BEST represent?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Discretionary Access Control (DAC)"},{"id":"b","text":"Multi-factor authentication (MFA)"},{"id":"c","text":"Role-based Access Control (RBAC)"},{"id":"d","text":"Mandatory Access Control (MAC)"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Requiring both a keycard (something you have) and a PIN (something you know) at the same entry point is a classic example of multi-factor authentication (MFA), combining two different authentication factors. DAC allows resource owners to control access at their discretion. RBAC assigns permissions based on a user's role within an organization. MAC enforces access based on classification labels and clearance levels. Neither DAC, RBAC, nor MAC specifically describes the combined use of multiple authentication factors at a physical entry point.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://pages.nist.gov/800-63-3/sp800-63b.html","label":"NIST SP 800-63B – Digital Identity Guidelines: Authentication"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Security+ & Server+ Physical Security Concepts"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator wants to protect a server room from unauthorized physical access by requiring both a keycard swipe AND a PIN entry at the same door. Which access control concept does this BEST represent?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company's Recovery Point Objective (RPO) is defined as 4 hours. What does this value indicate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The maximum amount of time the business can tolerate systems being offline after a failure"},{"id":"b","text":"The maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time before a disaster occurs"},{"id":"c","text":"The minimum time required to restore a full system backup"},{"id":"d","text":"The time between scheduled maintenance windows"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Recovery Point Objective (RPO) defines the maximum tolerable period in which data might be lost due to a major incident, measured in time. An RPO of 4 hours means the organization can afford to lose up to 4 hours of data. This drives decisions such as backup frequency—backups must run at least every 4 hours. Recovery Time Objective (RTO), not RPO, is the maximum tolerable downtime after a failure. RPO is not related to restore duration or maintenance windows.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/Legacy/SP/nistspecialpublication800-34r1.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-34 Rev. 1 – Contingency Planning Guide for Federal Information Systems"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives – Disaster Recovery"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company's Recovery Point Objective (RPO) is defined as 4 hours. What does this value indicate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which type of UPS topology uses the battery as the primary power source at all times, keeping the inverter constantly active and providing zero transfer time during a power outage?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Standby (offline) UPS"},{"id":"b","text":"Line-interactive UPS"},{"id":"c","text":"Double-conversion (online) UPS"},{"id":"d","text":"Ferro-resonant UPS"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$A double-conversion (online) UPS continuously converts incoming AC power to DC to charge the battery, then inverts it back to AC for the load. Because the load is always running from the inverter, there is zero transfer time during a power failure—the battery seamlessly takes over with no interruption. A standby UPS normally passes utility power and only switches to battery when an outage is detected, creating a small transfer time. A line-interactive UPS also has a brief transfer time and uses an autotransformer to regulate voltage. Ferro-resonant UPS units offer some conditioning but still have a transfer delay.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.se.com/us/en/work/campaign/life-is-on/ups-technology-comparison.jsp","label":"APC by Schneider Electric – UPS Topology Guide"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives – Power and Environmental"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which type of UPS topology uses the battery as the primary power source at all times, keeping the inverter constantly active and providing zero transfer time during a power outage?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization stores encrypted backup tapes at a third-party facility located 60 miles from the primary data center. Which disaster recovery site concept does this storage arrangement BEST describe?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Hot site"},{"id":"b","text":"Warm site"},{"id":"c","text":"Cold site"},{"id":"d","text":"Offsite tape vaulting"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["d"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Offsite tape vaulting refers to the practice of storing backup media (such as tapes) at a geographically separate, secure, third-party facility to protect against site-level disasters. This is not a hot, warm, or cold site—those terms describe alternate computing facilities with varying degrees of readiness (equipment, connectivity, data currency). Offsite tape vaulting is a media storage strategy, not an alternate processing site. A cold site would have physical space and power but no pre-installed equipment or current data.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/Legacy/SP/nistspecialpublication800-34r1.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-34 Rev. 1 – Alternate Storage Sites"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives – Disaster Recovery Sites"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization stores encrypted backup tapes at a third-party facility located 60 miles from the primary data center. Which disaster recovery site concept does this storage arrangement BEST describe?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server administrator is configuring a RAID array for a file server. Which RAID level provides fault tolerance by mirroring data across exactly two drives with no parity, giving the BEST read performance improvement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"RAID 0"},{"id":"b","text":"RAID 1"},{"id":"c","text":"RAID 5"},{"id":"d","text":"RAID 6"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$RAID 1 mirrors data identically across two drives, providing full fault tolerance—if one drive fails, the mirror contains an exact copy. Because reads can be serviced from either drive simultaneously, RAID 1 can improve read performance. RAID 0 stripes data for performance but offers zero fault tolerance. RAID 5 uses distributed parity across three or more drives and can survive one drive failure but involves parity overhead. RAID 6 uses dual parity across four or more drives and can survive two simultaneous drive failures. Neither RAID 5 nor RAID 6 uses simple two-drive mirroring.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives – Storage and RAID"},{"url":"https://www.snia.org/education/storage_networking_primer/stor_fund/raid_levels","label":"SNIA Dictionary – RAID Levels"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server administrator is configuring a RAID array for a file server. Which RAID level provides fault tolerance by mirroring data across exactly two drives with no parity, giving the BEST read performance improvement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which security framework concept describes the principle that each user or process should be granted only the minimum access rights necessary to perform their job function?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Separation of duties"},{"id":"b","text":"Least privilege"},{"id":"c","text":"Defense in depth"},{"id":"d","text":"Job rotation"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The principle of least privilege states that users, applications, and systems should be granted only the permissions required to perform their authorized tasks—nothing more. This minimizes the attack surface and limits damage from compromised accounts. Separation of duties requires that critical tasks be split among multiple people to prevent fraud or error. Defense in depth is a layered security strategy using multiple controls. Job rotation involves periodically reassigning staff to different roles to expose potential fraud and cross-train employees—it is a complementary but distinct concept from least privilege.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-53/rev-5/final","label":"NIST SP 800-53 Rev. 5 – AC-6 Least Privilege"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives – Security Concepts"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which security framework concept describes the principle that each user or process should be granted only the minimum access rights necessary to perform their job function?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator discovers that an attacker gained access to a server by exploiting a vulnerability in an unpatched service. Which security control, if implemented FIRST, would have MOST directly prevented this attack?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Installing a host-based intrusion detection system (HIDS)"},{"id":"b","text":"Applying the vendor-released security patch for the vulnerable service"},{"id":"c","text":"Enabling full-disk encryption on the server"},{"id":"d","text":"Configuring a network-based firewall to block all inbound traffic"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The attack exploited a known vulnerability in an unpatched service. Applying the vendor's security patch directly addresses and removes the vulnerability, which is the most direct preventive control. A HIDS can detect suspicious activity but does not prevent exploitation of an unpatched vulnerability before the attack succeeds. Full-disk encryption protects data at rest from physical theft but does not prevent remote exploitation of a running, vulnerable service. Blocking all inbound traffic would disrupt normal server operation and is not a targeted or practical fix—and the service may have been accessed through allowed ports anyway.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/SpecialPublications/NIST.SP.800-40r4.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-40 Rev. 4 – Guide to Enterprise Patch Management Planning"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives – Patch Management"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator discovers that an attacker gained access to a server by exploiting a vulnerability in an unpatched service. Which security control, if implemented FIRST, would have MOST directly prevented this attack?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A system administrator is setting up an environment where two servers share the same storage and one server takes over automatically if the primary fails with no manual intervention required. Which high-availability solution does this BEST describe?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Active-passive failover clustering"},{"id":"b","text":"Load balancing"},{"id":"c","text":"Cold standby"},{"id":"d","text":"Tape-based disaster recovery"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$An active-passive failover cluster consists of a primary (active) node handling all workloads and a secondary (passive) standby node that automatically takes over when the primary fails, typically sharing storage via a SAN or shared disk. This provides automatic failover with no manual intervention. Load balancing distributes traffic across multiple active servers but typically requires a separate mechanism to handle node failure. A cold standby requires manual activation and is not automatic. Tape-based disaster recovery involves restoring from backup, which requires significant time and manual effort—not automatic failover.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/failover-clustering/failover-clustering-overview","label":"Microsoft Learn – Windows Server Failover Clustering Overview"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives – High Availability"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A system administrator is setting up an environment where two servers share the same storage and one server takes over automatically if the primary fails with no manual intervention required. Which high-availability solution does this BEST describe?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which cryptographic protocol is MOST appropriate for encrypting data transmitted between a web browser and a server hosting an internal HR application to protect employee credentials in transit?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"SSH (Secure Shell)"},{"id":"b","text":"TLS (Transport Layer Security)"},{"id":"c","text":"IPSec in transport mode"},{"id":"d","text":"SFTP (SSH File Transfer Protocol)"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$TLS (Transport Layer Security) is the standard cryptographic protocol used to secure HTTP traffic (HTTPS) between web browsers and web servers. It provides encryption, integrity, and authentication for web application traffic, making it the correct choice for protecting credentials submitted through a browser to a web-based HR application. SSH is used for secure remote command-line access and file transfers, not browser-to-server web traffic. IPSec operates at the network layer and is typically used for VPN tunnels between network devices, not application-layer web sessions. SFTP is specifically for secure file transfers, not browser-based web application sessions.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8446","label":"RFC 8446 – The Transport Layer Security (TLS) Protocol Version 1.3"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives – Data Security in Transit"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which cryptographic protocol is MOST appropriate for encrypting data transmitted between a web browser and a server hosting an internal HR application to protect employee credentials in transit?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During a business continuity planning exercise, a team calculates how long a critical system can be offline before causing unacceptable business impact. Which term describes this maximum tolerable downtime?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Recovery Point Objective (RPO)"},{"id":"b","text":"Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF)"},{"id":"c","text":"Recovery Time Objective (RTO)"},{"id":"d","text":"Mean Time to Repair (MTTR)"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Recovery Time Objective (RTO) is the maximum acceptable length of time that a system or application can be offline after a disaster or disruption before the outage becomes unacceptable to the business. It drives decisions about redundancy, failover, and recovery procedures. RPO defines acceptable data loss in time, not system downtime. MTBF is a reliability metric expressing the average time between hardware or system failures. MTTR measures the average time needed to repair a failed component or system—it is a measurement of actual repair time, not a business planning target for acceptable downtime.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/Legacy/SP/nistspecialpublication800-34r1.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-34 Rev. 1 – Contingency Planning: RTO and RPO"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives – Business Continuity"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During a business continuity planning exercise, a team calculates how long a critical system can be offline before causing unacceptable business impact. Which term describes this maximum tolerable downtime?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator wants to prevent unauthorized USB storage devices from being connected to production servers. Which host-based security control BEST enforces this policy without requiring physical server modifications?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Physically filling unused USB ports with port blockers"},{"id":"b","text":"Configuring Group Policy to disable USB mass storage device drivers"},{"id":"c","text":"Enabling BitLocker encryption on the server's system drive"},{"id":"d","text":"Installing a host-based firewall on each server"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Configuring Group Policy (or an equivalent OS-level policy mechanism) to disable USB mass storage class drivers prevents the operating system from recognizing and mounting USB storage devices, enforcing the policy centrally without any physical hardware changes. Physical port blockers are a hardware control that requires physical access to install and can be removed. BitLocker encrypts the drive but does not prevent USB devices from being connected and recognized. A host-based firewall controls network traffic, not physical device connectivity. Group Policy-based USB control is scalable, reversible, and does not require physical server modification.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/troubleshoot/windows-client/group-policy/use-group-policy-to-install-software","label":"Microsoft Learn – How to Use Group Policy to Disable USB, CD, and Floppy Drives"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives – Physical and Logical Security"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator wants to prevent unauthorized USB storage devices from being connected to production servers. Which host-based security control BEST enforces this policy without requiring physical server modifications?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security administrator wants to verify that backup data can actually be used to restore a server to a working state. Which activity BEST accomplishes this goal?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Reviewing backup job completion logs in the backup software console"},{"id":"b","text":"Performing a test restore to an isolated environment and verifying application functionality"},{"id":"c","text":"Encrypting all backup media and storing them in a fireproof safe"},{"id":"d","text":"Increasing backup frequency from daily to hourly"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Performing a test restore to an isolated (non-production) environment and verifying that applications and data function correctly is the only way to confirm that backup data is valid, complete, and actually usable for recovery. Reviewing backup logs only confirms that the backup job ran and completed without reported errors—it does not verify data integrity or restorability. Encrypting and securing backups protects confidentiality but provides no assurance that the data can be successfully restored. Increasing backup frequency improves RPO but does not validate that existing backups are restorable.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/Legacy/SP/nistspecialpublication800-34r1.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-34 Rev. 1 – Testing Backup and Recovery Capabilities"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives – Backup Validation"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security administrator wants to verify that backup data can actually be used to restore a server to a working state. Which activity BEST accomplishes this goal?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which of the following BEST describes the purpose of an Intrusion Prevention System (IPS) compared to an Intrusion Detection System (IDS) in a server environment?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"An IPS only monitors and logs suspicious traffic, while an IDS actively blocks it"},{"id":"b","text":"An IPS can automatically block or drop malicious traffic inline, while an IDS only alerts administrators"},{"id":"c","text":"An IPS encrypts all server traffic, while an IDS decrypts and inspects it"},{"id":"d","text":"An IPS is software-only, while an IDS is always a hardware appliance"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$An Intrusion Prevention System (IPS) is deployed inline with network traffic and can actively block, drop, or quarantine malicious packets in real time without human intervention. An Intrusion Detection System (IDS) operates in passive (out-of-band) mode, analyzing a copy of traffic or host logs and generating alerts for administrators to review—but it takes no automatic blocking action. Neither system performs encryption or decryption as its primary function. Both IDS and IPS can be implemented as software, hardware, or hybrid solutions, making the hardware/software distinction in option D incorrect.$patch$, $patch$Security and Disaster Recovery$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/SpecialPublications/NIST.SP.800-94r1.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-94 Rev. 1 – Guide to Intrusion Detection and Prevention Systems"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives – Network Security"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which of the following BEST describes the purpose of an Intrusion Prevention System (IPS) compared to an Intrusion Detection System (IDS) in a server environment?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server administrator notices that a production server is randomly rebooting without generating a BSOD or kernel panic. The event logs show no critical errors immediately before the reboots. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause of this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Corrupt operating system files"},{"id":"b","text":"Failing power supply unit (PSU) providing unstable voltage"},{"id":"c","text":"Misconfigured RAID controller settings"},{"id":"d","text":"Outdated NIC firmware causing network drops"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Random reboots without BSOD or kernel panic and without critical event log entries are a classic symptom of unstable power delivery from a failing PSU. When voltage drops below required thresholds, the system resets abruptly — too fast for the OS to log an error or generate a dump. Corrupt OS files typically produce BSODs or panic messages. RAID misconfigurations cause I/O errors, not reboots. Outdated NIC firmware causes connectivity loss, not system reboots.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Study Guide – Power Subsystem Troubleshooting"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/troubleshoot/windows-server/performance/unexpected-restart","label":"Microsoft – Troubleshoot unexpected restarts"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server administrator notices that a production server is randomly rebooting without generating a BSOD or kernel panic. The event logs show no critical errors immediately before the reboots. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause of this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After replacing a failed hard drive in a RAID 5 array, the array begins rebuilding but performance degrades severely. Users report that the server is nearly unresponsive during the rebuild. Which of the following actions would BEST mitigate this situation while still completing the rebuild?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Abort the rebuild and restore from backup instead"},{"id":"b","text":"Throttle the RAID rebuild rate using the controller's management interface"},{"id":"c","text":"Remove all other drives from the array temporarily during rebuild"},{"id":"d","text":"Upgrade the RAID controller firmware before continuing"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Most enterprise RAID controllers provide a rebuild rate or priority setting that allows administrators to throttle how aggressively the controller uses disk and CPU resources during a rebuild. Lowering this setting reduces the performance impact on production workloads while still completing the rebuild. Aborting the rebuild leaves the array in a degraded state, increasing risk. Removing other drives would destroy the array. Upgrading firmware mid-rebuild is risky and does not directly address performance impact.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives – Storage Troubleshooting"},{"url":"https://docs.broadcom.com/doc/12353236","label":"Broadcom (LSI/Avago) MegaRAID Storage Manager User Guide – Rebuild Rate Settings"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After replacing a failed hard drive in a RAID 5 array, the array begins rebuilding but performance degrades severely. Users report that the server is nearly unresponsive during the rebuild. Which of the following actions would BEST mitigate this situation while still completing the rebuild?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server running Windows Server 2022 is experiencing high CPU utilization consistently above 95%. A technician opens Task Manager and finds that the System process is consuming most of the CPU. Which of the following tools would BEST help identify the specific driver or kernel component responsible?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Resource Monitor"},{"id":"b","text":"Windows Performance Recorder and Analyzer (WPA)"},{"id":"c","text":"Disk Management"},{"id":"d","text":"Server Manager Dashboard"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Windows Performance Recorder (WPR) captures an ETW trace and Windows Performance Analyzer (WPA) can break down CPU usage at the kernel and driver level, identifying exactly which driver or system component is consuming CPU time. Resource Monitor shows per-process CPU but cannot drill into kernel-mode threads within the System process at driver granularity. Disk Management and Server Manager are administrative tools that do not provide kernel-level CPU profiling.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/test/wpt/windows-performance-analyzer","label":"Microsoft Learn – Windows Performance Analyzer"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/test/wpt/windows-performance-recorder","label":"Microsoft Learn – Windows Performance Recorder"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server running Windows Server 2022 is experiencing high CPU utilization consistently above 95%. A technician opens Task Manager and finds that the System process is consuming most of the CPU. Which of the following tools would BEST help identify the specific driver or kernel component responsible?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A technician is troubleshooting a server that cannot PXE boot from the network. The DHCP server is confirmed to be operational. The technician captures traffic and confirms DHCP DISCOVER and OFFER packets are exchanged successfully, but the PXE client never downloads the boot image. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The NIC does not support Gigabit speeds"},{"id":"b","text":"The TFTP server is unreachable or not running"},{"id":"c","text":"The DHCP scope has been exhausted"},{"id":"d","text":"Secure Boot is preventing the OS from loading"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$PXE boot uses DHCP to obtain an IP address and the TFTP server address, then uses TFTP (UDP port 69) to download the boot image (NBP). If DHCP is working correctly but the image download fails, the issue is almost certainly with the TFTP service — it may be down, blocked by a firewall, or incorrectly configured. A non-Gigabit NIC would still support PXE at lower speeds. An exhausted DHCP scope would prevent the OFFER stage, which was confirmed working. Secure Boot restrictions affect OS loading after a successful PXE handoff.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 – Network Boot Troubleshooting"},{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc2132","label":"RFC 2132 – DHCP Options and BOOTP Vendor Extensions (option 66/67 for TFTP)"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A technician is troubleshooting a server that cannot PXE boot from the network. The DHCP server is confirmed to be operational. The technician captures traffic and confirms DHCP DISCOVER and OFFER packets are exchanged successfully, but the PXE client never downloads the boot image. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator receives alerts that a server's memory ECC error count has been steadily increasing over the past 72 hours. The server has not yet crashed. Which of the following is the MOST appropriate immediate next step?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Reboot the server to clear the ECC counters"},{"id":"b","text":"Schedule a maintenance window to identify and replace the failing DIMM"},{"id":"c","text":"Increase the page file size to compensate for memory errors"},{"id":"d","text":"Disable ECC reporting in BIOS to prevent false alerts"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Steadily increasing ECC error counts indicate a progressively failing DIMM. ECC can correct single-bit errors, masking crashes temporarily, but an increasing trend strongly predicts imminent uncorrectable errors leading to a system crash. The correct action is to schedule a maintenance window to use server management tools (e.g., iDRAC, iLO, IPMI) to identify which DIMM is failing and replace it before it causes data corruption or downtime. Rebooting only resets counters and does not fix the hardware. Increasing the page file is irrelevant. Disabling ECC reporting removes the only safety net and is dangerous.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.dell.com/support/kbdoc/en-us/000137307/understanding-and-resolving-memory-errors-on-poweredge-servers","label":"Dell Technologies – Understanding and Resolving ECC Memory Errors"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 – Memory Troubleshooting"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator receives alerts that a server's memory ECC error count has been steadily increasing over the past 72 hours. The server has not yet crashed. Which of the following is the MOST appropriate immediate next step?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux server's root filesystem is reporting 100% disk usage, but the administrator cannot find large files to delete using a standard directory size scan. Which of the following is the MOST likely explanation for the discrepancy?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The filesystem journal is corrupted and reporting incorrect usage"},{"id":"b","text":"One or more deleted files are still being held open by running processes"},{"id":"c","text":"The LVM logical volume needs to be extended"},{"id":"d","text":"RAID parity data is consuming additional filesystem space"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$On Linux, when a file is deleted while a process still has it open, the directory entry is removed (making it invisible to tools like du and ls), but the disk blocks are not released until the file descriptor is closed. This causes df to show used space that directory listings cannot account for. The fix is to identify the process using lsof to find open deleted files and restart or kill it to release the space. A corrupted journal would typically cause filesystem errors. LVM extension is a resolution, not a cause. RAID parity is managed below the filesystem level and does not consume filesystem space.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/solutions/2316","label":"Red Hat – Why does df and du report different free disk space?"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/lsof.8.html","label":"Linux man page – lsof(8)"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux server's root filesystem is reporting 100% disk usage, but the administrator cannot find large files to delete using a standard directory size scan. Which of the following is the MOST likely explanation for the discrepancy?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server's iDRAC (Integrated Dell Remote Access Controller) is accessible over the network, but the administrator is unable to establish a virtual console session to the server. The server itself is unresponsive to keyboard and mouse input on the physical KVM. Which of the following should the administrator try FIRST using the iDRAC?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Perform a graceful OS shutdown from the iDRAC power menu"},{"id":"b","text":"Issue an NMI (Non-Maskable Interrupt) to force a memory dump"},{"id":"c","text":"Use the iDRAC virtual console to view the current screen output and assess the server state"},{"id":"d","text":"Reset the iDRAC firmware to factory defaults"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Since the iDRAC is accessible, the first step should be to use its virtual console feature to view what is currently displayed on the server's screen. This provides critical diagnostic information — the server may be hung at a BSOD, kernel panic, POST error, or login prompt — before taking any action. Performing a shutdown without understanding the current state could cause data loss. Issuing an NMI is a drastic step used only when a memory dump is specifically needed for a hung OS. Resetting iDRAC firmware is irrelevant and destructive without cause.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.dell.com/support/manuals/en-us/idrac9-lifecycle-controller-v6.x-series/idrac9_6.xx_ug/overview-of-virtual-console","label":"Dell Technologies – iDRAC9 User's Guide – Virtual Console"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 – Remote Management Troubleshooting"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server's iDRAC (Integrated Dell Remote Access Controller) is accessible over the network, but the administrator is unable to establish a virtual console session to the server. The server itself is unresponsive to keyboard and mouse input on the physical KVM. Which of the following should the administrator try FIRST using the iDRAC?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A newly installed server fails to detect any installed drives during POST, even though the drives are physically seated and the power cables are connected. The RAID controller is listed in Device Manager. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The drives are formatted with a GPT partition table and the BIOS is in Legacy mode"},{"id":"b","text":"The data cables between the drives and the RAID controller are not connected or are faulty"},{"id":"c","text":"The server does not have enough RAM to support the number of drives installed"},{"id":"d","text":"The operating system has not been installed yet, preventing drive detection"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$If the RAID controller is recognized but no drives are detected during POST, the most probable cause is missing or faulty data connections (SAS/SATA cables or backplane connections) between the drives and the controller. Power cables being connected only provides power; data transfer requires separate data path connections. GPT vs. Legacy mode affects OS boot, not drive detection at the controller level. RAM quantity has no bearing on drive detection. Drives are detected during POST, before any OS is needed.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 – Storage Hardware Troubleshooting"},{"url":"https://www.seagate.com/support/kb/sas-and-sata-cabling-tips-193180en/","label":"Seagate – SAS and SATA Cabling Best Practices"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A newly installed server fails to detect any installed drives during POST, even though the drives are physically seated and the power cables are connected. The RAID controller is listed in Device Manager. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Users report intermittent connectivity to an application hosted on a server. A network administrator reviews interface statistics on the server's NIC and observes a high number of CRC errors on the receive side. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The NIC driver is outdated and needs to be updated"},{"id":"b","text":"A duplex mismatch between the server NIC and the upstream switch port"},{"id":"c","text":"A faulty physical cable or connector causing signal integrity issues"},{"id":"d","text":"The server's firewall is dropping inbound packets"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$CRC (Cyclic Redundancy Check) errors on the receive side indicate that frames are arriving with corrupted data, meaning the signal is being degraded in transit. The most common cause is a physical layer problem — a damaged cable, bent or dirty connector, or failing SFP/transceiver — that corrupts bits during transmission. A duplex mismatch typically causes late collisions and runts rather than CRC errors. Outdated drivers would cause functional issues, not signal-level corruption. A firewall drops packets cleanly without generating CRC errors at the NIC level.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/interfaces-modules/port-adapters/12768-eth-collisions.html","label":"Cisco – Troubleshooting Ethernet – CRC Errors"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 – Network Troubleshooting"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Users report intermittent connectivity to an application hosted on a server. A network administrator reviews interface statistics on the server's NIC and observes a high number of CRC errors on the receive side. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server running a critical database has been experiencing transaction log files growing to fill the entire data volume overnight. The database team confirms that transaction log backups are scheduled and completing successfully. Which of the following is the MOST likely reason the log files continue to grow unchecked?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The database is configured in SIMPLE recovery model, preventing log truncation"},{"id":"b","text":"A long-running open transaction is preventing log truncation after backups"},{"id":"c","text":"The backup software is using VSS snapshots instead of native log backups"},{"id":"d","text":"The data volume is formatted with FAT32, which has a 4 GB file size limit"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$In SQL Server (and many RDBMS), even if transaction log backups complete successfully, the log space cannot be reused (truncated) if there is a long-running or orphaned open transaction that began before the last log backup. The log must retain all records back to the oldest active transaction. SIMPLE recovery model actually enables automatic truncation at checkpoints, not prevents it. VSS snapshots for consistent database backups can coexist with log backups. FAT32 is never used for production database volumes and is irrelevant.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/sql/relational-databases/logs/the-transaction-log-sql-server#FactorsThatDelayTruncation","label":"Microsoft Learn – Factors that can delay log truncation (SQL Server)"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 – Storage and Application Troubleshooting"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server running a critical database has been experiencing transaction log files growing to fill the entire data volume overnight. The database team confirms that transaction log backups are scheduled and completing successfully. Which of the following is the MOST likely reason the log files continue to grow unchecked?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server administrator is troubleshooting a server that experiences a kernel panic shortly after booting into Linux. The panic message references a module loaded during the initramfs stage. After reviewing recent change logs, the administrator finds that a storage driver was updated the previous evening. Which of the following is the BEST recovery approach?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Boot from a live CD, chroot into the environment, and rebuild the initramfs with the previous driver version"},{"id":"b","text":"Reinstall the operating system to restore the original driver state"},{"id":"c","text":"Replace the physical storage controller with an older model"},{"id":"d","text":"Boot the server in Windows PE to roll back the Linux driver"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When a kernel panic is caused by a faulty module in the initramfs, the proper recovery is to boot from external media (live CD/USB), chroot into the installed OS environment, roll back or remove the problematic driver package, and rebuild the initramfs (using dracut or mkinitramfs) so the system can boot cleanly. A full OS reinstall is unnecessarily destructive and time-consuming. Replacing physical hardware does not address a driver/software issue. Windows PE cannot manage Linux filesystem or driver configurations.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/solutions/1958","label":"Red Hat – How to rebuild the initramfs"},{"url":"https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Grub2/Troubleshooting","label":"Ubuntu Documentation – Recovering a system with a broken initramfs"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:sk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$SK0-005-P4$patch$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server administrator is troubleshooting a server that experiences a kernel panic shortly after booting into Linux. The panic message references a module loaded during the initramfs stage. After reviewing recent change logs, the administrator finds that a storage driver was updated the previous evening. Which of the following is the BEST recovery approach?$patch$);
